<CATEGORY> washington </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Clinton Ark. Homecoming Said Cold </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	WASHINGTON (AP) -- Arkansas' Democratic faithful were finished  
paying tribute to retired Sen. Dale Bumpers. Dinner long had been 
eaten. The hugs and handshakes tapered off and the clock ticked 
ever closer to midnight. 
</P>
<P>
	Still, President Clinton, set to fly back to the White House  
after the festivities ended, lingered among his friends late 
Saturday night, joking that he hung out so long, ``we've doubled 
the price of rice.'' 
</P>
<P>
	So long that the crowd had dwindled from several hundred to just  
nine, and the lights began going out in Little Rock's cavernous 
Statehouse Convention Center. 
</P>
<P>
	Clinton ventured near the television cameras, getting more hugs  
that create the warm-fuzzy footage associated with the private 
moments of legendary people. 
</P>
<P>
	``Hello guys,'' Clinton called to the TV crews waiting to  
accompany him to Washington. ``Let's GO, Mr. President!'' came the 
reply from a lone voice in the back. 
</P>
<P>
	It was a bittersweet weekend return to his roots, full of rain  
and solitude, for a man whose visit was built around the dedication 
of his birth home in Hope. 
</P>
<P>
	His brother and childhood pals were there, but his wife and  
daughter were not, and Clinton looked a little lonely. The visit 
was cut short by a day, and the nearly constant rain left Clinton's 
schedule loose and somewhat aimless. 
</P>
<P>
	``The weather was sad, but otherwise it was OK,'' was Clinton's  
assessment of the trip, as he ambled back to Air Force One's rear 
galley for a beverage during the flight to Washington. 
</P>
<P>
	Clinton's daughter Chelsea, a sophomore at Stanford University,  
remained at school. First lady Hillary Rodham Clinton was in 
Washington, sidelined still, the president said, by the back injury 
that also led her to skip his Central American trip last week. She 
needs the rest so that she and Chelsea can tour North Africa later 
this month, the president said. 
</P>
<P>
	``She wanted to go to Central America, she wanted to go to  
this,'' Clinton said. ``I've got to make sure, she's got to make 
sure, she's a little bit healthier for Africa.'' 
</P>
<P>
	After capping his Friday stop in Hope by paying a water-sogged  
visit to his mother's grave, Clinton went to Texarkana, Texas, to 
help raise money for Rep. Max Sandlin, a supporter during 
impeachment. He spent the night on the Wamba, Texas, cattle ranch 
of businessman Truman Arnold. 
</P>
<P>
	Saturday, it was too rainy and cold for him to play golf so  
Clinton lounged at Arnold's home. 
</P>
<P>
	In the afternoon, Clinton flew to Little Rock, got off his plane  
in a gust of wind and a layer of rain on the tarmac -- ``Cold!'' he 
shouted -- and went directly to the home of his mother-in-law, 
Dorothy Rodham. 
</P>
<P>
	He watch his beloved Arkansas Razorbacks take on Iowa in the  
NCAA basketball tournament. 
</P>
<P>
	Arkansas lost.  
</P>
<P>
	Clinton then attended a $200,000 Democratic National Committee  
reception before the Bumpers event, and mingled with folks who told 
him their confidence in him was never shaken. 
</P>
<P>
	At the Bumpers dinner, Arkansas' politicos worked to make up for  
Clinton's lack of immediate family. Sen. David Pryor called Clinton 
before he left Arnold's ranch, and Clinton asked Pryor to fill him 
in on the crowd he would be addressing. 
</P>
<P>
	``I said, 'Mr. President, this is your family. These are your  
people, and these are the people who love you,''' Pryor said. 
</P>
<P>
	A somber tone in his voice, Clinton said he understood that -- it  
was evident in the spirited defense summation that Bumpers 
delivered before the Senate at Clinton's impeachment trial. 
</P>
<P>
	Though they have long known each other, Bumpers and Clinton were  
not considered extremely close. 
</P>
<P>
	In his first Senate primary in 1974, Bumpers defeated Clinton's  
mentor, Sen. William Fulbright. During his first presidential term, 
Clinton turned more often to Pryor for advice. 
</P>
<P>
	Clinton said he and Bumpers had been through ``all kinds of  
adversity'' together, and that he would miss being able to reach 
out across town to Bumpers ``when I get real low.'' 
</P>
<P>
	``Mr. President, I may not be your best friend in the Senate,''  
Bumpers said Saturday night. ``But you're the best friend I've had 
in the Oval Office.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Saturday night, Clinton and Bumpers put their heads together in  
conversation as the lights dimmed for a video tribute. Suddenly, 
the president stopped talking and nodded in time with a song 
playing over a montage of images from Bumpers' long career: 
</P>
<P>
	``Count on me and I'll count on you ... Now and always we will  
be good friends.'' 
</P>
<P>
	When the song ended, Clinton turned to Bumpers and resumed their  
chat. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
