<CATEGORY> usa </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> La. Church Empty After Shooting </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	GONZALES, La. (AP) -- The little white church where three people  
died in a hail of bullets last week was empty Sunday, while 200 of 
its members shook off the winter chill and bad memories in a civic 
center miles away. 
</P>
<P>
	Pastor Clarence Stephens likened the sudden violence that  
interrupted the New St. John Fellowship's Bible study on Wednesday 
to a storm sent by God as a test. 
</P>
<P>
	``A pre-warned storm shows how well you can prepare,'' Stephens  
shouted Sunday. ``But an unexpected storm -- follow me now -- an 
unexpected storm will show your true strengths and weaknesses.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Shon Miller, who is in his 20s, is accused of bursting into the  
church and opening fire, killing his wife, Carla Vessel Miller, 24, 
and son, Shon Jr., 2. He is charged with first-degree murder and 
attempted murder. 
</P>
<P>
	A 19-year-old church member, Vaniaro Jackson, also was killed in  
the gunfire and police later found Carla Miller's mother, Mildred 
Vessel, 53, shot in her car near the church. Miller is accused of 
ambushing his mother-in-law before heading into the church. Four 
people were wounded in the church. 
</P>
<P>
	Church leaders decided last week they will hold no more services  
at the church. They are raising money to complete electrical work 
and other interior details on a new building nearby, but that could 
take months. In the meantime, decisions on where to worship will be 
made week to week. 
</P>
<P>
	At least one of the four people wounded was present for Sunday's  
services. 
</P>
<P>
	Donald Rideau, 16, hobbled along on crutches.  
</P>
<P>
	``I didn't realize I was shot at first,'' he said. Then, he  
said, he began sweating profusely and feeling dizzy. And ``my mama 
noticed there was a hole in my pants.'' 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
