<HEADLINE> AP Top News at 10 p.m. EST  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	Report: Baptist Leader To Resign  
</P>
<P>
	ST. PETERSBURG, Fla. (AP) -- The Rev. Henry Lyons, convicted of  
swindling $4 million as head of the National Baptist Convention, 
U.S.A., is sorry for bringing shame to the church and indicated he 
will resign, according to ABC's ``20/20 Monday.'' Lyons said that 
he will step down even if the church group's board of trustees does 
not ask him to resign. ``I think it's best,'' Lyons told Connie 
Chung in an interview scheduled to air Monday. Lyons was convicted 
last month of racketeering for swindling more than $4 million from 
corporations seeking to do business with the convention. 

</P>
<P>
	Fleet Deal To Create 8th Largest Bank  
</P>
<P>
	NEW YORK (AP) -- Fleet Financial Group Inc. is planning to  
acquire BankBoston Corp. for $16 million in stock, but the move may 
force the loss of 5,000 jobs. The deal will give Fleet a stronger 
investment banking arm while giving BankBoston the muscle it needs 
to compete against bigger financial institutions. The combined bank 
will be named Fleet Boston Corp., and it will be the dominant 
lender in New England. But overlapping branches and administrative 
operations will force the loss of jobs. 

</P>
<P>
	GOP Pressing on China Spy Case  
</P>
<P>
	WASHINGTON (AP) -- Republicans are insisting on answers following  
the Clinton administration's admitting today that China gained 
valuable information about nuclear technology allegedly stolen from 
a Los Alamos lab. Senior GOP senator, Dick Lugar of Indiana, 
recommended a ``very serious review'' of the country's China 
policy. Lugar also said on NBC's ``Meet the Press'' that the United 
States should make clear to China that it will defend Taiwan from a 
Chinese missile attack. 

</P>
<P>
	U.S. Prison Population Growing  
</P>
<P>
	WASHINGTON (AP) -- The number of adult prisoners in the United  
States has more than doubled since 1985, and the U.S. may soon 
surpass Russia as the country with the highest rate of 
incarceration. The Justice Department said today that at mid-1998, 
jails and prisons held an estimated 1.8 million people, according 
to a Bureau of Justice Statistics report. At the end of 1985, the 
figure was 744,208. 

</P>
<P>
	Snowstorm Rolling Across East Coast  
</P>
<P>
	BALTIMORE (AP) -- A storm that dumped nearly two feet of snow in  
Missouri and claimed several lives in Oklahoma moved to the East 
Coast today, lashing states with snow, sleet and rain. More than a 
foot of snow has fallen in areas of Maryland tonight, while most of 
the state was getting a slushy mixture of snow and rain. 

</P>
<P>
