<HEADLINE> US Women's Team Ties Sweden 1-1 </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	LISBON, Portugal (AP) -- Tiffeny Milbrett's goal 15 minutes into  
the game was all the favored United States could manage Sunday in a 
1-1 tie with Sweden in the opening round of the Algarve Cup. 
</P>
<P>
	The international women's soccer tournament, a tuneup for this  
year's World Cup in the United States, features six nations that 
will participate in the World Cup, starting June 19. 
</P>
<P>
	The Americans had defeated Sweden nine consecutive times dating  
back to November 1991. And they got off to a good start. 
</P>
<P>
	Julie Foudy, who played a slick and creative match in midfield,  
sent a perfect pass to Mia Hamm on the right side. Hamm drove to 
the net and sent a hard cross on the ground through the goalmouth. 
Shannon MacMillan caught a small piece of the ball, but Milbrett 
sliced her shot into the left corner from 8 yards. 
</P>
<P>
	The goal was Milbrett's first of 1999 and 48th of her career.  
</P>
<P>
	The U.S. team paid for its inability to finish in the 76th  
minute when Sweden tied it. Malin Mostrom got loose on the right 
wing on a counterattack and crossed to the far post, where 
substitute Linda Fagerstrom volleyed the ball in from 4 yards. 
</P>
<P>
	Despite more than doubling Sweden's shot total, 19-8, the U.S.  
team could not punch in another goal. 
</P>
<P>
	``We did a lot of things well and we were unfortunate to give up  
that goal on what was really just one of two chances they got in 
the second half,'' coach Tony DiCicco said. ``But we didn't finish 
our chances and I'm disappointed at that. 
</P>
<P>
	``But Ulrika Karlsson once again made several world-class saves  
and I think she was responsible for the result that they were able 
to get.'' 
</P>
<P>
	U.S. veteran Michelle Akers came on at halftime, marking her  
first action since she broke her left cheekbone against the FIFA 
World Stars last month. 
</P>
<P>
	In other games Sunday, China beat Portugal 4-0, Denmark and  
Australia tied 1-1, and defending world champion Norway downed 
Finland 1-0. 
</P>
