<CATEGORY> political </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Report: N.J. Gov. To Run for Senate </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	TRENTON, N.J. (AP) -- Gov. Christie Whitman has decided to run  
for U.S. Senate in 2000, according to a newspaper report Sunday. 
</P>
<P>
	Citing unnamed Republican sources, The Trentonian reported that  
Whitman will seek the GOP's nomination for the seat being vacated 
by retiring Democrat Frank Lautenberg. 
</P>
<P>
	Whitman spokesman Peter McDonough denied that the governor has  
made definite plans. 
</P>
<P>
	McDonough said Whitman's decision will depend on how quickly she  
can reach the three main objectives of her second term: a 
billion-dollar property tax rebate program, a million acres of 
open-space preservation and whole-school reform. 
</P>
<P>
	``The question now is whether or not she could get these  
accomplished before she would have to depart for Washington should 
she run'' for Senate, McDonough said. 
</P>
<P>
	McDonough said Whitman will announce her intentions within a few  
weeks after her trip to South America, where she is heading a 
10-day New Jersey trade mission. 
</P>
<P>
	Lautenberg unexpectedly announced his retirement last month.  
Republican leaders in New Jersey and nationwide have urged Whitman 
to run for the seat. 
</P>
<P>
	Whitman's decision may set up a rematch with former Gov. Jim  
Florio, a Democrat whom Whitman unseated in 1993. Florio is 
expected to seek the Democratic nomination to succeed Lautenberg. 
</P>
</TEXT>
