<DOCNO> APW19990314.0013 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-03-14 13:21:39 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> sports </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Kjus Wins World Cup Title </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	SIERRA NEVADA, Spain (AP) -- The friendship between Lasse Kjus  
and Kjetil Andre Aamodt couldn't be closer. 
</P>
<P>
	World Cup roommates for 10 years, they're both 28 and, along  
with retired Marc Girardelli, they've each won a record 13 Olympic 
and World Championship medals. 
</P>
<P>
	When the World Cup year ended Sunday, they were together again,  
separated by only 23 points in the overall standings -- one of the 
tightest men's finishes on record -- with Kjus claiming the coveted 
season title. 
</P>
<P>
	``Today there will be a great party, and I'll drink everyone  
under the table,'' Kjus said. 
</P>
<P>
	``The only thing I can do is congratulate Lasse,'' Aamodt said.  
``He has been the best skier all season. For what he did here and 
what he did in the Worlds (last month), I can only take my hat off 
to him.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Kjus, who underwent sinus surgery two years ago and has coughed  
and wheezed all winter with a chest infection, sped to a quick 
second leg in Sunday's giant slalom to grab seventh -- after being 
15th after the first -- to clock a combined 2 minutes, 5.48 seconds. 
</P>
<P>
	Needing a second place to earn enough points to overtake Kjus,  
Aamodt got only fifth in 2:05.13. Kjus finished with 1,465 points 
and Aamodt 1,442 in a season that spans three-dozen men's races 
over 4 1/2 months. 
</P>
<P>
	Kjus won six World Cup races -- five in downhill and a combined.  
Aamodt won only a combined. 
</P>
<P>
	Last month in Vail, Colo., Kjus became the first man to win five  
medals in a World Championships, including gold in super-G (shared 
with Hermann Maier) and giant slalom. 
</P>
<P>
	``It is unbelievable to get this title,'' said Kjus, who won the  
same one in '96. ``It was great fun to have this close fight with 
Kjetil. I felt a lot of pressure in the second run because I had 
made so many mistakes on the first. But I risked it all because I 
had to.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Aamodt said he stopped rooming with Kjus on the World Cup  
circuit last year ``because we got like an old married couple.'' 
</P>
<P>
	``We'd said about all two people could to each other in that  
time,'' said Aamodt, who won the 1994 World Cup overall. 
</P>
<P>
	The Kjus-Aamodt 1-2 was the closest men's overall finish since  
1991 when Girardelli nipped Alberto Tomba by 20 points. But that 
was under a scoring system that awarded many fewer points -- as was 
the 1980 title when four points separated the winners. 
</P>
<P>
	Under the system begun in the 1991-92 season, the closest men's  
finish prior to Sunday's near-dead heat was in 1993 when Girardelli 
edged Aamodt by 32 points. 
</P>
<P>
	In addition to deciding the overall, the season giant slalom  
title was also settled Sunday with Michael Von Gruenigen of 
Switzerland winning the race and season title. 
</P>
<P>
	Von Gruenigen won in 2:04.33, followed by fellow countryman  
Steve Locher in 2:04.40 and Heinz Schilchegger of Austria in third 
in 2:04.44. Von Gruenigen finished with 483 points to 410 for 
Austrian Stephan Eberharter and 371 for defending champion Maier. 
</P>
<P>
	Maier, who said he aggravated a back injury in Saturday's slalom  
and needed painkiller injections to ski Sunday, went out five gates 
from the finish on the first leg, losing his right ski -- and temper 
in the process. 
</P>
<P>
	He stormed by reporters and spoke only briefly to Austrian  
television. 
</P>
<P>
	The defending overall World Cup and giant slalom champion, Maier  
was eliminated from the chase in Saturday's slalom, finishing 
behind Kjus and Aamodt with 1,307 points. 
</P>
<P>
	``I was disappointed about the situation and just didn't feel  
very coordinated,'' said the two-time Olympic champion. ``When I 
went out, I didn't even realize what had happened. My back was even 
worse today than it was yesterday.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Kjus' title Sunday ended a World Cup season dominated by  
Austrian women. They won all five titles -- a feat last accomplished 
in 1987 by the Swiss women. 
</P>
<P>
	Alexandra Meissnitzer took the overall, downhill and super-G  
with Renate Goetschl taking downhill and Sabine Egger the crystal 
globe in slalom. 
</P>
<P>
	Meissnitzer clinched super-G and Egger her slalom when the two  
races were canceled last week by high winds and snowstorms in 
Europe's southernmost ski resort. 
</P>
<P>
	On the men's side, the Austrians -- after sweeping all five last  
season -- got a super-G title from Maier and a slalom title from 
Thomas Stangassinger, at 33 the oldest skier on the circuit. Kjus 
won both overall and downhill with Von Gruenigen taking giant 
slalom. 
</P>
</TEXT>
