<CATEGORY> financial </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Credit Lyonnais Privatization OK'd </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	PARIS (AP) -- The French government has authorized the  
privatization of the ailing Credit Lyonnais bank, the French 
Finance Ministry said Sunday. 
</P>
<P>
	Credit Lyonnais lost $3.7 billion between 1992 and 1994 and a  
state bailout package approved earlier this year cost French 
taxpayers nearly $18 billion. 
</P>
<P>
	The expected announcement comes at a time of great turmoil in  
the French banking sector. Last week the Banque Nationale de Paris 
made a surprise $37.2 billion takeover bid for rivals Paribas SA 
and Societe Generale SA. 
</P>
<P>
	Under the terms of the privatization plan, the French government  
would maintain a 10 percent stake in Credit Lyonnais. Ten percent 
of the bank's shares already have been floated. 
</P>
<P>
	The decree calls for the creation of a core shareholder of  
institutional investors, who will be allowed to hold less than one 
third of the bank's shares. 
</P>
<P>
	After consultations with unions and employers, a ``significant  
share of capital'' of Credit Lyonnais will be made available to 
them. A subsequent stock offering will take place in June. 
</P>
<P>
	A limited number of potential partners for Credit Lyonnais are  
available, given the ongoing battle among Banque Nationale de 
Paris, Societe Generale and Paribas. 
</P>
<P>
	The Credit Agricole said Friday it will seek to participate in  
the privatization of Credit Lyonnais. French insurance company AXA 
and the German insurance company Allianz -- via its French 
subsidiary AGF -- also have expressed interest. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
