<CATEGORY> usa </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Lawyer Faces Murder Sentencing </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	WILMINGTON, Del. (AP) -- Thomas Capano moved in exclusive  
circles. 
</P>
<P>
	The oldest son in a wealthy family, he became a lawyer who fit  
in easily among Delaware's social, political and legal elite. He 
advised a mayor and a governor, even toying with the idea of 
running for attorney general. 
</P>
<P>
	But Capano had a dirty, little secret: multiple mistresses and  
an obsessive need to control them. 
</P>
<P>
	When one of those mistresses -- the governor's scheduling  
secretary -- tried to break away, he killed her. On Tuesday, the 
former state prosecutor could join another exclusive circle: death 
row. 
</P>
<P>
	The prospect of Capano's execution seemed almost fantastic to  
those who knew him, considering the 49-year-old lawyer's standing 
in the community. But reality is sinking in. 
</P>
<P>
	``Sometimes, having wealth gives an arrogance that you can  
control things and get away with things and cover them over,'' said 
Thomas Maloney, a former Wilmington mayor who has known Capano for 
years. ``And as long as he didn't have a breach, he would have been 
safe.'' 
</P>
<P>
	The sentencing judge has two choices: the death penalty or life  
in prison. 
</P>
<P>
	Jurors in January convicted Capano of the murder of Anne Marie  
Fahey, although prosecutors never found the body. Jurors voted 10-2 
to recommend that Capano be executed -- a strong recommendation that 
a state judge would seldom disregard. 
</P>
<P>
	During his three-month trial, Capano showed little of the acumen  
that helped him become a trusted adviser to former Wilmington Mayor 
Daniel Frawley and legal counsel to former Gov. Michael Castle. 
Rejecting his lawyers' advice, he took the witness stand when he 
could have remained silent. He lost his cool more than once, 
exploding at prosecutors and pouting when the judge reprimanded 
him. 
</P>
<P>
	Prosecutors offered no theory about how Ms. Fahey died on June  
27, 1996. They instead set about proving that Capano had planned 
her death and then gotten rid of the body by stuffing it in a 
cooler and dumping it in the Atlantic Ocean from his brother's 
boat. 
</P>
<P>
	After 2 1/2 years of silence about what happened that night, Capano  
stunned the courtroom by admitting that she died at his house and 
he got rid of her body. But he blamed another mistress, Deborah 
MacIntyre, whom he said accidentally killed Ms. Fahey in a jealous, 
suicidal rage. 
</P>
<P>
	Ms. MacIntyre denied the accusation. And the jury rejected his  
story. 
</P>
<P>
	Prosecutors said Capano killed because his mistress wanted to  
end their secret, three-year affair. 
</P>
<P>
	Capano had been the jealous one, according to Ms. Fahey's diary.  
After she started someone else, Capano became ``a controlling, 
manipulative, insecure, jealous maniac,'' she wrote. 
</P>
<P>
	The controlling nature extended to others close to him who later  
worked with prosecutors. A brother, Gerard Capano, testified about 
helping get rid of a body. Another brother, Louis, said Thomas 
asked him to get rid of potential evidence. 
</P>
<P>
	Ms. MacIntyre said Capano had her buy him a gun before Ms. Fahey  
disappeared. 
</P>
<P>
	From prison, Capano wrote letters and made calls to Ms.  
MacIntyre demanding her loyalty. When those failed, he wrote up 
plans for her house to be burglarized. 
</P>
<P>
	``This was like a guy controlling the puppets,'' Maloney said.  
``But all the strings broke.'' 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
