<CATEGORY> entertainment </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Mob Comedy Rubs Out Competition / Box Office  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	LOS ANGELES (AP) -- Neurotic gang boss Robert De Niro and his  
therapist Billy Crystal held off a flood of new movies as ``Analyze 
This'' remained atop of the box office chart for a second week. 
</P>
<P>
	Appealing to older audiences in a market full of teen fare,  
``Analyze This'' collected an impressive $15.7 million, down just 
15 percent from its debut weekend, according to industry estimates 
released Sunday. 
</P>
<P>
	That placed the mob comedy far ahead of the second-place film,  
the belated horror sequel ``The Rage: Carrie 2,'' which opened with 
$7.4 million. 
</P>
<P>
	``Cruel Intentions,'' a mean tale of love games starring Sarah  
Michelle Gellar, tumbled 46 percent in its second week to finish 
third with $7 million, according to studio estimates for gross 
receipts for Friday through Sunday. 
</P>
<P>
	Final numbers were scheduled to be released today.  
</P>
<P>
	``Rage,'' a follow-up to the original ``Carrie'' in 1976, led a  
whopping list of five new films that opened in wide release over 
the weekend. But with a tepid per-location average of $3,237 and 
the usual short shelf life for horror pictures, ``Rage's'' days may 
be numbered. 
</P>
<P>
	Indeed, all the newcomers opened to fair to lackluster business,  
and the box office overall was once again down -- this time 6.3 
percent -- from the same weekend last year when ``Titanic'' was 
sailing into record grosses. 
</P>
<P>
	One mild surprise was ``Baby Geniuses,'' a critically panned  
film about scientists who find that baby-talk is more than it 
seems. Apparently taking advantage of a lack of children's movies 
in theaters, ``Geniuses'' far exceeded Sony's modest expectations 
to open with $5.8 million. 
</P>
<P>
	Of the other new movies, the police buddy film ``The  
Corruptor,'' pairing Hong Kong action star Chow Yun-Fat with Mark 
Wahlberg, debuted with $5.9 million for fourth, the Michelle 
Pfeiffer kidnapping drama ``The Deep End of the Ocean'' opened with 
$5.6 million for sixth and the movie version of the popular 
computer game ``Wing Commander'' had $5 million for seventh. 
</P>
<P>
	Holdovers rounded out the Top 10.  
</P>
<P>
	``The Other Sister,'' a love story about a mentally challenged  
couple, had $3.9 million for eighth, the disturbing thriller 
``8mm'' with Nicolas Cage continued its free-fall after a big 
opening with $3.6 million for ninth and the rocketry story 
``October Sky'' continued to do steady business with $3.1 million 
for 10th. 
</P>
<P>
	Among the contenders for best picture Academy Award on March 21,  
``Shakespeare in Love'' had $2.8 million and ``Life is Beautiful'' 
had $1.9 million. 
</P>
<P>
	Here are estimated three-day weekend grosses at North American  
theaters. 
</P>
<P>
	1. ``Analyze This,'' $15.7 million.  
</P>
<P>
	2. ``The Rage: Carrie 2,'' $7.4 million.  
</P>
<P>
	3. ``Cruel Intentions,'' $7 million.  
</P>
<P>
	4. ``The Corruptor,'' $5.9 million.  
</P>
<P>
	5. ``Baby Geniuses,'' $5.8 million.  
</P>
<P>
	6. ``The Deep End of the Ocean,'' $5.6 million.  
</P>
<P>
	7. ``Wing Commander,'' $5 million.  
</P>
<P>
	8. ``The Other Sister,'' $3.9 million.  
</P>
<P>
	9. ``8mm,'' $3.6 million.  
</P>
<P>
	10. ``October Sky,'' $3.1 million.  
</P>
