<CATEGORY> sports </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Kenya's Bor Wins L.A. Marathon </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	LOS ANGELES (AP) -- Simon Bor of Kenya won the Los Angeles  
Marathon in 2 hours, 9 minutes, 25 seconds Sunday, beating 
countryman James Bungei and breaking the 11-year-old course record 
in only his third marathon. 
</P>
<P>
	Irina Bogacheva of Kyrgyzstan sped past Svetlana Zakharova of  
Russia with about five miles remaining to win the women's division 
in 2:30:32. 
</P>
<P>
	Bor, who ran a 4:56 mile pace, bettered the old mark of 2:10:19  
set by Martin Mondragon of Mexico in 1988. Bor's time was slower 
than his personal best of 2:08:46 for 26.2 miles. 
</P>
<P>
	Bor earned $60,000, including a $25,000 bonus for the record,  
and a new car in continuing the trend of Kenyans dominating in Los 
Angeles. They took six of the top 10 spots in last year's marathon. 
</P>
<P>
	``Whenever you go and do something good, it means you have done  
something good for your country,'' Bor said. ``To my fellow Kenyans 
back at home, they are very happy. I have managed to do what they 
were expecting from me.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Bungei, who trains in Albuquerque, N.M., completed his first  
major marathon in 2:10:43. He won three half-marathons last year. 
</P>
<P>
	``My goal was just to finish,'' Bungei said. ``I knew it was  
hard.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Bor ran with training partner Christopher Cheboiboch of Kenya  
for more than half the race before moving in front at the 19-mile 
mark, just before the course reached its highest point in a series 
of hills. Cheboiboch said he had malaria for the past 12 days. 
</P>
<P>
	``When my friend was trouble, it was the time I was gaining  
momentum,'' Bor said. ``I had to go without him.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Bungei passed Cheboiboch for second place after 23 miles.  
Cheboiboch finished at 2:13:49. 
</P>
<P>
	Bogacheva, who won marathons in Belgrade and Honolulu last year  
and finished second at Los Angeles in 1997, trains part-time in 
Gainesville, Fla. She earned $40,000, including a $5,000 bonus for 
going under 2:32:00, and a new car. 
</P>
<P>
	``I'm so happy,'' she said. ``Today is my lucky day.''  
</P>
<P>
	Zakharova, who ran alone on the lead for several miles, was  
timed at 2:32:54, followed by Alla Zhilayeva of Russia at 2:33:41. 
</P>
<P>
	``The main thought was finish the race, no matter how difficult  
it is,'' Zakharova said through a translator. 
</P>
<P>
	Lornah Kiplagat of Kenya failed to win for a third straight  
year, dropping out after 10 miles. She was later diagnosed with a 
lung infection. 
</P>
<P>
	``At the start, I was feeling OK,'' she said. ``After four  
miles, it was very hard to breathe. When I was at six miles, I 
started coughing.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Organizers said there were about 20,600 participants.  
</P>
</TEXT>
