<CATEGORY> usa </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Report: Bapist Leader To Resign </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	ST. PETERSBURG, Fla. (AP) -- The Rev. Henry Lyons, convicted of  
swindling $4 million as head of the National Baptist Convention, 
U.S.A., is sorry for bringing shame to the church and indicated he 
will resign, according to ABC's ``20/20 Monday.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Lyons said during an interview with Connie Chung that he will  
step down even if the church group's board of trustees does not ask 
him to resign. 
</P>
<P>
	``I think it's best,'' Lyons told Chung in an interview  
scheduled to air Monday. ``The emphasis now must be on the church, 
on the convention, on the programs and mission and ministries of 
the convention.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Lyons, 57, was convicted last month of racketeering for  
swindling more than $4 million from corporations seeking to do 
business with the convention. He also was convicted of grand theft 
for stealing nearly $250,000 donated by the Anti-Defamation League 
of B'Nai B'rith to rebuild burned black churches in the South. 
</P>
<P>
	``I don't know that there's any one reason I did not give it  
out,'' he said of the $250,000. ``I don't think I'll ever recover 
from that mistake.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Prosecutors said Lyons and his co-defendant Bernice Edwards  
duped companies into paying for a membership mailing list that did 
not exist, then went on lavish spending sprees -- buying a huge 
diamond ring, waterfront home, several luxury cars and expensive 
clothing. 
</P>
<P>
	Ms. Edwards was acquitted of racketeering. Lyons will be  
sentenced March 31 and faces three to seven years in prison. 
</P>
<P>
	In a separate federal case, Lyons faces 54 charges of extortion,  
tax evasion, conspiracy and fraud. Jury selection in that trial is 
scheduled to begin next month, but Lyons has reportedly been 
discussing a plea agreement with prosecutors. 
</P>
<P>
	``I've spent the last 18, 19, 20 months, uh, repenting,  
repenting, repenting ... over and over again,'' he told Chung. ``I 
have said to my god: 'I am sorry.' You gave the opportunity of my 
life, one that I sought for all my life. You blessed me and I 
cursed you back.'' 
</P>
</TEXT>
