<CATEGORY> usa </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Snowstorm Moves Across East Coast </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	BALTIMORE (AP) -- A storm that dumped nearly two feet of snow in  
Missouri and claimed several lives in Oklahoma moved to the East 
Coast Sunday, lashing states with snow, sleet and rain. 
</P>
<P>
	More than a foot of snow fell in areas of Maryland by early  
Sunday night, while most of the state was getting a slushy mixture 
of snow and rain. New Jersey and New York were seeing small amounts 
of snows. 
</P>
<P>
	The same storm system hit the Midwest hard over the weekend.  
</P>
<P>
	In Missouri, about 23 inches of snow fell from Saturday into  
Sunday morning in the southwestern part of the state, stranding 
many motorists. 
</P>
<P>
	In Oklahoma, 18 inches of snow fell in some spots, causing  
dozens of traffic accidents in the northern part of the state 
Saturday. At least 13 people were killed in weekend traffic 
accidents, officials said. 
</P>
<P>
	On Sunday, the weather was blamed for a pileup on Interstate 70  
in Maryland involving more than 20 vehicles -- including buses, 
tractor trailers and at least 15 cars and trucks. None of the 
injuries was life-threatening, police said. 
</P>
<P>
	Two of the buses were carrying high school band members from St.  
Louis. The band was returning to Missouri after performing in the 
Baltimore and Washington areas. 
</P>
<P>
	Snow emergency plans were in effect in several counties. Despite  
the conditions, the St. Patrick's Day Parade went on as scheduled 
in downtown Baltimore. 
</P>
<P>
	Laura Beeman, 21, a server at the Tombstone Cafe in Frostburg,  
in western Allegany County, said the storm was worst so far this 
year. 
</P>
<P>
	``Last year, there wasn't any time that people got snowed into  
their houses. Pretty much no one's getting their car out,'' she 
said. 
</P>
<P>
	In New Jersey, where as much as 10 inches of snow was forecast,  
the storm arrived early Sunday night. 
</P>
<P>
	``A lot of people forget you can get significant snow in  
March,'' said Anthony Gigi, a meteorologist with the National 
Weather Service's Mount Holly office. 
</P>
<P>
	In Kentucky, snow and sleet caused havoc on the roads. About a  
half-foot of wet, heavy snow fell in northern Kentucky, near 
Cincinnati. 
</P>
<P>
	Gary Hensley, a roads foreman for the Kenton County Department  
of Public Works, said the wintry blast didn't deter people from 
getting out. 
</P>
<P>
	``They're still going to the mall. They're still going to the  
store,'' he said. 
</P>
<P>
	State police reported numerous accidents but no major traffic  
tie-ups. 
</P>
<P>
	In Pennsylvania, several inches of snow and rain fell throughout  
the state. Nearly two feet fell in Somerset County in southwestern 
Pennsylvania. 
</P>
<P>
	In Ohio, more than a foot fell in the southern part of the  
state, which was the heaviest snowfall of the season in some 
communities. Numerous flights were delayed at the 
Cincinnati/Northern Kentucky International Airport. 
</P>
<P>
	West Virginia saw heavy snowfall in some areas: Morgantown saw  
10 inches and about a foot fell in Preston County, which was 
expecting as much as 18 inches. Dozens of accidents were reported. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
