<CATEGORY> washington </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Chicago U. Sued for Alleged Fraud </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	CHICAGO (AP) -- The federal government has accused the University  
of Chicago of purposely overbilling Medicare and Medicaid claims 
for its medical center. 
</P>
<P>
	A lawsuit filed in U.S. District Court alleges the university  
made a habit of ``upcoding,'' or billing at a higher rate than was 
warranted by the procedures performed. 
</P>
<P>
	It contends that about 40 percent of the university's most  
expensive Medicare claims between 1991 and 1997 were upcoded, the 
Chicago Tribune reported in its Sunday editions. 
</P>
<P>
	The government alleges the abuse was blatant and not accidental.  
</P>
<P>
	``We deny any allegations of improper billing to Medicare or any  
other payer,'' hospital spokesman John Easton told the Tribune. 
</P>
<P>
	The university, the U. of C. Physicians Group and the University  
of Chicago Hospitals are named as defendants in the lawsuit. 
</P>
<P>
	The lawsuit does not set an amount for damages. But private  
attorneys involved in the case have told the Tribune it could cost 
the university as much as $100 million. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
