<CATEGORY> political </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Gore Finally Steps Out on His Own </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	WASHINGTON (AP) -- Vice President Al Gore is kicking off his  
White House bid with the first official political trip of his 2000 
campaign, hoping to begin stepping outside President Clinton's 
shadow and prove his worth against potential Republican rivals. 
</P>
<P>
	Gore was visiting New Hampshire and Iowa on a one-day swing  
today to address supporters in states that are critical to winning 
the Democratic presidential nomination. 
</P>
<P>
	Gore's only announced opponent for the nomination is former New  
Jersey Sen. Bill Bradley, although civil-rights activist Jesse 
Jackson is considering the race. Opting out in recent weeks were 
House Minority Leader Dick Gephardt and three senators who could 
have offered stiff challenges. 
</P>
<P>
	Bradley, a Hall of Fame basketball player, says he can beat Gore  
one-on-one and win the general election. 
</P>
<P>
	He hopes to capitalize on Democrats' concern about Gore's poll  
numbers. Although the vice president is maintaining a healthy lead 
over Bradley among Democratic voters, he is not fairing as well 
against Republican favorite George W. Bush. 
</P>
<P>
	The latest Wall Street Journal-NBC poll shows Gore 18 percentage  
points behind the Texas governor. 
</P>
<P>
	A Pew Research Center survey found nearly half of independent  
voters and 16 percent of Democratic voters have ruled out voting 
for Gore. The same poll showed that 76 percent of independents and 
53 percent of Democrats say they would consider voting for Bush. 
</P>
<P>
	Gore says he's not worried about polls conducted ``four  
lifetimes'' before the election. 
</P>
<P>
	``If I were the Gore campaign I would be concerned,'' said  
Democratic consultant David Axelrod of Chicago. ``But I wouldn't 
panic.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Democratic operatives say Gore's two biggest challenges are  
showing that he can be a leader after years as Clinton's understudy 
and convincing Americans that he cares about their problems. 
</P>
<P>
	With those goals in mind, Gore planned to roll out a new stump  
speech to promote initiatives not necessarily part of the 
administration agenda. Promising to make ``revolutionary changes in 
our schools,'' he was calling for reduced class sizes in all 
grades. Clinton had focused on elementary schools. 
</P>
<P>
	The vice president also wants to make preschool available  
everywhere in the country. 
</P>
<P>
	Gore is staking out territory in poll-tested health care issues,  
promising more preventive care options. ``Instead of more breast 
cancer tomorrow, let's have more mammograms today. Instead of more 
low-birthweight babies tomorrow, let's have more prenatal care 
today. Instead of more sick children tomorrow, let's have more 
immunizations today,'' his stump speech says. 
</P>
<P>
	Last week, Gore worked from the White House to lay claim to a  
series of bite-size initiatives popular among suburban voters, such 
as promising to ease traffic jams. Fine ideas, Democrats say, but 
he needs to leave Washington to promote his own agenda. 
</P>
<P>
	``I'm not sure about that ribbon-cutting strategy. That one  
makes me nervous,'' Axelrod said. ``I think it just underscores the 
second-banana thing.'' 
</P>
<P>
	``That's the disease that all vice presidents have: You cannot  
be seen as a strong, decisive leader when you're the second man on 
the totem pole,'' said Democratic pollster Mark Mellman. 
</P>
<P>
	Gore's biggest advantage, the support of a popular president,  
was being put on display today as he continued to collect 
endorsements from party stalwarts. Bill Shaheen, husband of New 
Hampshire Gov. Jeanne Shaheen, will formally join the Gore team. In 
Iowa, 70 prominent Democrats are set to side with the vice 
president. Gov. Shaheen and Iowa Gov. Tom Vilsack are still 
neutral. 
</P>
<P>
	Republicans say Gore won't escape Clinton's policies or  
controversies. 
</P>
<P>
	``He is the Velcro to Clinton's Teflon,'' said GOP media  
strategist Alex Castellanos. ``A lot of problems that slide off of 
Clinton stick to Gore.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Gore proved last week that is prone to gaffes of his own. He  
claimed that he created the Internet, giving Republicans reason to 
howl. 
</P>
<P>
	Gore has done political chores on previous trips, but this is  
the first one in which his campaign organization will pick up part 
of the tab. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
