<CATEGORY> sports </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Lankford, Renteria May Be Out </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	JUPITER, Fla. (AP) -- Last spring, the St. Louis Cardinals were  
burdened with pitching problems. This year, they're looking a bit 
shaky up the middle. 
</P>
<P>
	Shortstop Edgar Renteria and center fielder Ray Lankford, two  
key players who figured to have healed from injuries a long time 
ago, may not be ready for opening day. Renteria is supposed to be 
the leadoff hitter and Lankford will bat cleanup. 
</P>
<P>
	Renteria, acquired from the Florida Marlins in the offseason,  
hasn't played this spring because of a knee bruise that first 
sidelined him last August. The physical exam he took in January 
after the trade appeared to show he was on the mend, but when he 
arrived at training camp in mid-February the knee was worse. 
</P>
<P>
	``Yeah, we're concerned about it,'' general manager Walt  
Jocketty said. ``Our doctors are still trying to determine exactly 
what the course of action should be.'' 
</P>
<P>
	The Cardinals began last season without starting pitchers Matt  
Morris, Donovan Osborne and Alan Benes, and a team that was 
supposed to contend in the NL Central never recovered. As for this 
year's most pressing problem, Manager Tony La Russa said he didn't 
know which player was closer to being ready. 
</P>
<P>
	``Good question,'' La Russa said. ``They both may be tied for  
last.'' 
</P>
<P>
	The game plan calls for Renteria, 23, who hit .282 with 41  
steals last season, to begin playing sometime next week. But that's 
only if the knee comes around. Right now there's no pain but he's 
unable to run with his normal gait, which leaves the team to wonder 
what happened the month after he signed. 
</P>
<P>
	An MRI last week showed only a knee bruise.  
</P>
<P>
	``We'll find out,'' Jocketty said. ``We don't have the answer  
yet.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Renteria has remained optimistic about his situation, at least  
outwardly. 
</P>
<P>
	``I've been waiting a long time and I'm getting stronger,'' he  
said. ``I'll be all right.'' 
</P>
<P>
	One thing the Cardinals do know is they have no complaint with  
the Marlins over the trade, despite giving up right-hander Braden 
Looper, left-hander Armando Almanza and shortstop prospect Pablo 
Osuna. 
</P>
<P>
	Looper is expected to make the Marlins as a setup man, Almanza  
could make it as a left-handed reliever and Osuna is considered one 
of the jewels of the Florida system and will start the season at 
Double-A Portland. 
</P>
<P>
	``We did not receive damaged goods,'' Jocketty said.  
</P>
<P>
	Lankford, coming off a career-best 105 RBIs, angered team  
officials in January when he underwent arthroscopic knee surgery on 
his own to clear up what was believed to be a minor problem. The 
team allowed him to recuperate on his own program until the last 
few days, when it was evident things weren't moving as swiftly as 
anticipated. 
</P>
<P>
	``We gave him as much flexibility as we could to let him follow  
his program, his course of action,'' Jocketty said. ``It's not 
working and he's on our program now.'' 
</P>
<P>
	So far, Lankford has played only two games this spring and both  
have been as a designated hitter against American League teams. 
</P>
<P>
	``He's not able to play defense yet, and that's what concerns  
us,'' Jocketty said. ``He can't start and stop the way he should.'' 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
