<CATEGORY> sports </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Lindros Drops the Gloves </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	PHILADELPHIA (AP) -- Not tough enough? In one of their biggest  
statement games in years, the Philadelphia Flyers waited only 40 
seconds to try to fight themselves out of their 10-game winless 
slump. 
</P>
<P>
	Amid criticism from the owner's box to the locker room that the  
Flyers have lost their toughness, captain Eric Lindros dropped the 
gloves in the opening minute of Philadelphia's game against 
NHL-leading Dallas on Sunday night. The Flyers were trying to avoid 
tying a franchise-record 11-game winless streak. 
</P>
<P>
	Lindros, one of the best fighters in the NHL who rarely fights,  
put a rattling check on Stars captain Derian Hatcher. They fought 
and skated to the penalty box. 
</P>
<P>
	Before the puck was dropped for the ensuing faceoff,  
Philadelphia's Colin Forbes and Pat Verbeek of Dallas took swipes 
at each other and were sent off for high-sticking. Reflecting the 
importance of this nationally televised game, the First Union 
Center roared to life as a breathless Lindros put his gloves back 
on in the box. 
</P>
<P>
	Less than a minute later, Philadelphia's Roman Vopat fought  
Grant Marshall in the Philadelphia zone. With three minutes left in 
the first period, Lindros was in the middle of a multi-player 
scuffle at the side of the Dallas net. 
</P>
<P>
	The Flyers, 0-7-3 in their last 10 games, have been in an  
inexplicable freefall since dropping out of the Eastern Conference 
lead last month. They haven't won since beating Pittsburgh 2-1 
three weeks ago Sunday. 
</P>
<P>
	The Flyers have had two 11-game winless streaks in franchise  
history -- in 1968-69 and 1970-71 seasons, going 0-9-2 both times. 
</P>
<P>
	General manager Bob Clarke had a closed-door meeting with the  
team a few hours before game time. The meeting came days after team 
chairman Ed Snider questioned the Flyers' toughness and said, ``I 
think this team has had a complete mental collapse.'' 
</P>
<P>
	``Sometimes a different voice telling them the same thing  
helps,'' said Clarke, adding that coach Roger Neilson agreed that 
the GM should address the club. 
</P>
<P>
	``Roger and I talked, and we both thought it was a good idea,''  
Clarke said. 
</P>
<P>
	Clarke has tried everything -- from reacquiring former Flyer Mark  
Recchi to bringing up minor league goaltender Jean-Marc Pelletier 
for one game. 
</P>
<P>
	``On paper we have good players,'' Clarke said. ``But even our  
top players are doing things now they don't normally do. No one is 
confident.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Clarke said the team has canceled a planned vacation to New  
Orleans. The team had been planning to take a few days off after 
playing at St. Louis on Tuesday. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
