<DATE_TIME> 1999-03-14 15:32:40 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> usa </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Police Probe Package Left at Church </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	NEW YORK (AP) -- Tourists and worshippers trying to enter St.  
Patrick's Cathedral Sunday morning were briefly turned away while 
police investigated a suspicious package which turned out to be a 
bundle of digital devices programmed to flash the word 
``homophobic.'' 
</P>
<P>
	The package was discovered by a parishioner on a pew at 11 a.m.,  
near the end of a morning Mass, normally conducted by Cardinal John 
J. O'Connor. 
</P>
<P>
	A bomb squad was sent in to retrieve the plastic bags,  
containing devices police described as some sort of alarm clock. 
They were sent to a police laboratory for testing, said Officer 
LeeAnn Tracy. 
</P>
<P>
	People were turned away while police investigated, but the noon  
Mass was not delayed. 
</P>
<P>
	St. Patrick's Cathedral and O'Connor have been targeted for  
criticism in recent years by gays and lesbians demanding the right 
to march as a group in the annual St. Patrick's Day parade. 
</P>
<P>
	This year's parade will be Wednesday.  
</P>
</TEXT>
