<CATEGORY> usa </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> AP Top News at Midnight EST  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	Fleet Plans To Acquire BankBoston  
</P>
<P>
	NEW YORK (AP) -- Fleet Financial Group Inc. plans to acquire  
BankBoston Corp. for $16 billion in stock in a deal that will 
create the nation's eighth-largest bank. The combined bank, to be 
named Fleet Boston Corp., will be the dominant lender in New 
England. However, faced with overlapping branches and 
administrative operations, Fleet Boston may have to cut as many as 
5,000 jobs from their total work force of 59,000, executives said 
Sunday. 

</P>
<P>
	Report: Baptist Leader To Resign  
</P>
<P>
	ST. PETERSBURG, Fla. (AP) -- The Rev. Henry Lyons, convicted of  
swindling $4 million as head of the National Baptist Convention, 
U.S.A., is sorry for bringing shame to the church and indicated he 
will resign, according to ABC's ``20/20 Monday.'' Lyons said that 
he will step down even if the church group's board of trustees does 
not ask him to resign. ``I think it's best,'' Lyons told Connie 
Chung in an interview scheduled to air Monday. Lyons was convicted 
last month of racketeering for swindling more than $4 million from 
corporations seeking to do business with the convention. 

</P>
<P>
	Snowstorm Lashes East Coast  
</P>
<P>
	BALTIMORE (AP) -- A storm rolled across the East Coast Sunday,  
lashing states with snow, sleet and rain. The same storm system hit 
the Midwest hard over the weekend dumping nearly two feet of snow 
in Missouri. Several people died in weather-related accidents in 
Oklahoma. More than a foot of snow fell in areas of Maryland by 
early Sunday night, while most of the state was getting a slushy 
mixture of snow and rain. New Jersey and New York were seeing small 
amounts of snows. 

</P>
<P>
	Istanbul Rocked by Second Attack  
</P>
<P>
	ISTANBUL, Turkey (AP) -- A bomb blast under a truck in Istanbul  
killed at least one person and wounded five others Sunday, a day 
after an arson attack left 13 people dead, media reports said. 
Explosive experts defused a second bomb planted inside a crowded 
Burger King fast-food restaurant on the outskirts of the city, the 
Anatolia news agency said. Police tightened security following a 
string of bombings and arson attacks that have gripped Turkey since 
the capture of Kurdish rebel leader Abdullah Ocalan by Turkish 
forces in Kenya on Feb. 15. Ocalan faces trial on charges of 
treason and a possible death sentence. 

</P>
<P>
	Study Links Smoking, Adult Crime  
</P>
<P>
	CHICAGO (AP) -- Babies whose mothers smoke during pregnancy could  
be at a higher risk of growing up to be criminals, new research 
suggests. Researchers say a study published in this month's 
Archives of General Psychiatry is the first to examine the 
relationship between mothers who smoke and their children's adult 
behavior. The researchers -- from Emory University in Atlanta, the 
University of Southern California and the Institute of Preventive 
Medicine in Denmark -- found that more a quarter of the men whose 
mothers had the highest levels of smoking and delivery 
complications were arrested for a violent crime as an adult. 

</P>
<P>
	Suspicious Bag at Airport Probed  
</P>
<P>
	COLUMBUS, Ohio (AP) -- The FBI is investigating whether former  
federal transportation inspector general Mary Schiavo violated any 
laws when she checked a suspicious bag at an airport here to test 
security measures, officials said Sunday. Ms. Schiavo, a former 
inspector general of the Department of Transportation, checked a 
bag Friday at Port Columbus International Airport as part of a 
story WCMH-TV was doing on airport security. The bag's discovery 
led to a shutdown of a runway for four hours yesterday, but no 
flights were delayed. 

</P>
<P>
	Tokyo Stocks Slip in Early Trading  
</P>
<P>
	TOKYO (AP) -- Japanese stocks slipped in early trading Monday  
following the release of gloomy data about the nation's economy. 
The Nikkei shed 15.27 points to 15,473.59 points in the first 30 
minutes of trading. 

</P>
<P>
	Lakers Lose Without Rodman  
</P>
<P>
	SACRAMENTO, Calif. (AP) -- Already missing Dennis Rodman, the Los  
Angeles Lakers lost their perfect record under Kurt Rambis on 
Sunday night as Jason Williams' 21 points led the Sacramento Kings 
to a 105-101 win over the Lakers. Despite 33 points by Shaquille 
O'Neal and 29 by Kobe Bryant the Lakers had their 10-game winning 
streak snapped by a Kings team that had lost its previous three 
games. Rambis had tied an NBA record by winning his first nine 
games as Lakers coach. Rodman was granted an indefinite leave of 
absence for unspecified personal reasons just as the Lakers began a 
six-game road trip. 

</P>
<P>
	Duke Routs Tulsa 97-56  
</P>
<P>
	NEW YORK (AP ) -- Top-seeded Duke routed Tulsa 97-56 in the  
second round of the NCAA tournament Sunday. Temple upset Cincinnati 
64-54, eliminating the only team to beat Duke this season and 
Oklahoma ousted NC-Charlotte 85-72. Southwest Missouri State earned 
its first trip to the round of 16 with a 81-51 win over Tennessee. 
Purdue upset second-seeded Miami to reach the regional semifinals 
for the second straight year. 

</P>
<P>
	AP NewsBrief by STEPHANIE GASKELL  

</P>
