<CATEGORY> usa </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> 5-Time Escapee Returned to Prison </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	COLLINSVILLE, Ala. (AP) -- DeKalb County Sheriff Cecil Reed was  
finally able to relax in his office and watch ``America's Most 
Wanted.'' Less than an hour before the show aired, the fugitive he 
had asked to be profiled was back in custody. 
</P>
<P>
	Authorities found Roger Dale Yeadon, 26, a five-time prison  
escapee, hiding in the attic of a friend's rural home about 45 
minutes before ``America's Most Wanted'' showed his picture 
Saturday. 
</P>
<P>
	Yeadon had been sentenced to more than 18 years behind bars in  
the fatal carjacking of a British military man. ``We thought for 
several days he was in our area, and when we watched it on TV, it 
felt really good,'' Reed said Sunday. 
</P>
<P>
	U.S. Marshals took Yeadon to Jefferson County Jail in  
Birmingham, where he is scheduled for a hearing today in federal 
court. He was to be handed over to authorities from New Mexico 
after the hearing. 
</P>
<P>
	Yeadon escaped from a jail in Las Vegas, N.M., Feb. 8. He, along  
with two other inmates who were later recaptured, shinnied up pipes 
leading to the jail's roof, authorities said. 
</P>
<P>
	He traveled to Alabama by bus and went to the northeast corner  
of his home state, where he has relatives. Authorities set up 
electronic listening posts and later used helicopters and tracking 
dogs in the search, said Mike Richards, a supervisor at the U.S. 
Marshal's office in Birmingham. 
</P>
<P>
	A tip Saturday night led them to the home in the rural community  
of Skirum, near Collinsville, said Reed. The convict surrendered 
without resistance at 7:15 p.m. Fox's ``America's Most Wanted'' 
aired locally at 8 p.m. 
</P>
<P>
	``When I found him in that room, he put up his hands, turned  
around and went down on his knees,'' Deputy Sheriff Lt. Jimmy 
Harris said. ``He said, 'I ain't going nowhere. I've been through 
this before.''' 
</P>
<P>
	Yeadon, who had grown a beard to alter his appearance, had a  
small pocket knife when captured, a handcuff key in his boot and 
was concealing a small amount of marijuana, Reed said. 
</P>
<P>
	He also had tried to alter his tattoo of the Ford Motor Co. logo  
to make it look like a pile of bricks, said Tom Bustamante, chief 
deputy U.S. marshal in Albuquerque, N.M. 
</P>
<P>
	Yeadon was sentenced in January to more than 18 years in federal  
prison for the 1996 carjack slaying of Maj. David Graham Nichols, 
vice commander of the Defence School of Languages in England, who 
was killed en route to a conference at Kirtland Air Force Base in 
Albuquerque. 
</P>
<P>
	At the time of the carjacking, Yeadon was an escapee from  
Alabama. 
</P>
<P>
	His latest escape came from the San Miguel County Jail in Las  
Vegas, N.M., where he was being held pending assignment to a 
federal prison. 
</P>
<P>
	Yeadon had apparently been sleeping in the woods or abandoned  
houses for the past month, living on foliage and vegetables from 
gardens, said Mike Richards, a supervisory deputy marshal based in 
Birmingham. 

</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
