<DOCNO> APW19990314.0054 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-03-14 09:51:53 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> usa </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Cops: Man Faked Death, Killed Man </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	LaFOLLETTE, Tenn. (AP) -- The body inside the burning Ford Tempo  
was charred beyond recognition by the time sheriff's deputies 
arrived. 
</P>
<P>
	The car, which had plunged down an embankment and come to rest  
about 30 feet off U.S. 25 near the Kentucky border, belonged to 
47-year-old Joseph Prewitt of nearby Stinking Creek, and his 
grieving family buried him in a cemetery here five days before 
Christmas. 
</P>
<P>
	But 3 1/2 weeks later, police found Prewitt hiding in an apartment  
in Corbin, Ky., about 30 miles north on Interstate 75. He's now in 
the Campbell County jail, awaiting a Tuesday hearing on charges of 
kidnapping, arson and first-degree murder, all linked to an alleged 
plot to collect $1 million in life insurance. 
</P>
<P>
	Marie Prewitt, his wife of 15 years, doesn't believe any of it.  
</P>
<P>
	``They are portraying Joe as this monster,'' she says. ``He is a  
good father. A kind person. A gentle person. He would never hurt 
anybody.'' 
</P>
<P>
	The body in the car was actually that of Charles Wayne Bryant,  
26, of Williamsburg, Ky. Prewitt and a friend of Bryant's -- Bobby 
Canada, 38 -- are charged with first-degree murder in his death. 
</P>
<P>
	The state plans to seek the death penalty against Prewitt and  
Canada. Prewitt's attorney, assistant public defender Charles 
Herman, will comment only to note his client is not the only person 
charged. 
</P>
<P>
	Before the Dec. 15 car crash and Jan. 8 arrest, Prewitt was best  
known in the local mountain towns for losing his teaching job with 
a lie. In the early 1980s, he taught math at Wynn High School and 
coached the girls' basketball team to its first state tournament 
appearance. But he was forced to resign in 1985 when authorities 
discovered he'd lied about having a degree from Cumberland College 
in Kentucky. 
</P>
<P>
	After that, he worked a variety of jobs before going on  
disability. 
</P>
<P>
	Some months ago, Prewitt began spreading the word that he had an  
inoperable brain tumor, investigators say. On Dec. 15, he told his 
family he had a doctor's appointment in Lexington, Ky. Later that 
day, a passer-by alerted deputies to the burning car. 
</P>
<P>
	``Some things didn't look right,'' says chief Sheriff's Deputy  
Bobby Vann. ``It went through our minds that he had had a car wreck 
and got killed. It went through our minds that maybe he committed 
suicide. 
</P>
<P>
	``There was something that didn't look right, but we didn't have  
anywhere else to go with the investigation. We didn't have a victim 
anywhere else. ... We had nothing to say it wasn't him because the 
body was unidentifiable.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Vann explains that Dr. Cleland Blake, a forensic expert who does  
autopsies for Campbell County, ``took what we gave him and said, 
`Well, the body is the same (size as Prewitt's). It is burnt beyond 
recognition. There are no fingerprints to compare. So until we get 
DNA back, we are going to have to say it is (Prewitt).''' 
</P>
<P>
	Two and a half weeks after ``Prewitt'' was buried, with DNA test  
results still pending, Tennessee investigators learned Charles 
Bryant had disappeared the same day the burning car was found. They 
got permission to exhume the body. 
</P>
<P>
	Blake compared dental records and determined the dead man was  
Bryant. The second autopsy also found Bryant had been hit on the 
head and shot, Vann says. Blake declined an interview with The 
Associated Press. 
</P>
<P>
	``He was still alive when he was burned, but the fire didn't  
kill him,'' Vann says. ``He would have died from the gunshots.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Investigators discovered Prewitt had taken out several life  
insurance policies totaling about $1 million in the six months 
before his supposed death. 
</P>
<P>
	Some of the most telling evidence against Prewitt apparently  
comes from members of his family. They told investigators a lawyer 
claiming to represent Prewitt's estate began calling them to 
instruct them they should send future insurance checks to a post 
office box in Caryville, Tenn. 
</P>
<P>
	They were told ``it would be a criminal offense if they didn't  
do it,'' Vann says. The relatives became suspicious and, as 
conversations with the lawyer grew more involved, they believed 
they recognized the voice as Prewitt's. Investigators obtained a 
tape recording of at least one conversation for voice analysis. 
</P>
<P>
	None of the calls were to Marie Prewitt, and authorities are  
convinced Mrs. Prewitt had no clue about the alleged insurance scam 
or murder. 
</P>
<P>
	Vann will not say how police located Prewitt. He and Canada were  
arrested Jan. 8. The woman whose apartment Prewitt was using as a 
hiding place has been identified only as a former girfriend of 
Canada. She has not been charged. 
</P>
<P>
	But a second woman, Kay Doan, 35, of Corbin, was charged as an  
accessory Jan. 11. According to an affidavit from agent Charles 
Scott of the Tennessee Bureau of Investigation, Doan says she saw 
Prewitt and Canada push the car with Bryant inside over an 
embankment, splash it with gasoline and light it. She also ``saw 
Prewitt with blood on him,'' the affidavit says. 
</P>
<P>
	Prewitt, whose previous court file contains nothing more serious  
than passing bad checks and defaulting on a car loan, appears to 
have plotted the crime for some time, Vann says. The deputy cites 
Prewitt's recent complaints of depression and claims he was dying 
of the brain tumor. 
</P>
<P>
	``I think that was exactly what his plan was -- to fake his own  
death,'' Vann says. ``I don't know if he had a victim picked out 
yet or not, but he was setting it up.'' 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
