<CATEGORY> sports </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> NCAA Midwest Regional Notebook </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	NEW ORLEANS (AP) -- Coach Charlie Coles was busy overseeing Miami  
of Ohio's upset of No. 2 seed Utah NCAA Midwest Regional Sunday, a 
win that got the Redhawks to the round-of-16 for the first time 
ever. 
</P>
<P>
	Not too busy, though, to forget an anniversary.  
</P>
<P>
	``I had been out of the hospital exactly a week on this day last  
year,'' Coles said. 
</P>
<P>
	Coles had a heart attack on Feb. 28, 1998, during a game against  
Western Michigan, and had to have his heart electrically shocked to 
restart it. 
</P>
<P>
	Coles said his perspective on life has changed since the  
incident, but his attitude about basketball has only grown 
stronger. 
</P>
<P>
	He celebrated each of his team's tournament wins, but kept them  
in perspective. 
</P>
<P>
	``It's fun. It feels really good,'' Coles said. ``But there's  
always another game.'' 
</P>
<P>
                            	 *------	 
</P>
<P>
	 *UK-KU ANNUALLY?:* Two of the winningest teams in college  
basketball haven't played in consecutive seasons since 1990. 
</P>
<P>
	Kansas coach Roy Williams says that could change -- but that it  
would be a few years before his Jayhawks and Kentucky schedule any 
kind of series. 
</P>
<P>
	Williams said he and Kentucky coach Tubby Smith, long-time  
friends, have talked about a future series. 
</P>
<P>
	``We both have too many series now,'' Williams said. ``I decided  
that I'm not going to accept any more series. We'll finish the 
contracts we have and look at it again down the road.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Williams said the series was discontinued in 1990 by  
then-Kentucky coach Rick Pitino. 
</P>
<P>
	``I would have been in favor of keeping it. But like a marriage,  
both parties have to agree,'' Williams said. 
</P>
<P>
	Kentucky and Kansas played in the Midwest Regional on Sunday. It  
was the first postseason meeting ever between the two powers. 
</P>
<P>
                            	 *------	 
</P>
<P>
	 *STREAK STOPPED:* Utah had its 23-game winning streak end with  
the loss to Miami in the Regional. The Utes' streak was second only 
to Duke's 28 in a row. The last three years, Utah lost its final 
game to Kentucky, last year, in the championship game. 
</P>
<P>
                            	 *------	 
</P>
<P>
	 *BLACK PATCHES:* Kentucky's players wore black patches on their  
jerseys to mark the death of death of Wildcats recruit John 
Stewart. 
</P>
<P>
	The 7-foot Stewart, who was from Lawrence North High School in  
Indianapolis, signed with the Wildcats in November. He died Friday 
night after collapsing during a state tournament game. 
</P>
<P>
                            	 *------	 
</P>
<P>
	 *WRONG CONTAINER:* Just minutes into Sunday's first game at the  
Midwest Regional, an NCAA official went along press row asking 
media members to take their bottled waters off the table -- and out 
of view. 
</P>
<P>
	The plastic Aquafine water bottles were available in the media  
work room from the company that provided water at the event. Behind 
both benches were water buckets with NCAA and Aquafine emblems on 
them. 
</P>
<P>
	But press members courtside were handed plastic cups with NCAA  
logos and told to keep the bottles under the table. 
</P>
<P>
                            	 *------	 
</P>
<P>
	 *SWOOP MASCOTS:* The courtside mascots for Utah and Miami of  
Ohio, could pass for long-lost cousins. Both bird-like figures were 
named Swoop. 
</P>
<P>
	The Miami RedHawks mascot has a red body, silver head and big  
yellow beak. He wore a No. 0 jersey with his name on the back. 
</P>
<P>
	The Utes mascot, donning a No. 96 jersey with the same name, had  
a brown body. He also outdid his fellow mascot at halftime, getting 
on five-foot stilts and passing a football between people in the 
Superdome crowd. 
</P>
<P>
                            	 *------	 
</P>
<P>
	 *TURNER LONGEVITY:* Kentucky guard Wayne Turner, who has missed  
just one game in his college career, played in his 149th game on 
Sunday. 
</P>
<P>
	Turner broke the national record held by Duke's Christian  
Laettner. 
</P>
<P>
	Laettner, by the way, was the last of three Duke players to  
participate in four Final Fours -- from 1989-92. 
</P>
</TEXT>
