<DOCNO> APW19990314.0059 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-03-14 17:31:41 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> sports </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> NFL Owners Undecided on Expansion </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	PHOENIX (AP) -- Los Angeles? Houston? Nowhere?  
</P>
<P>
	As team owners gathered Sunday for the NFL meetings, questions  
about the possible home for the league's possible 32nd team drew 
responses that were all over the map. 
</P>
<P>
	Robert McNair, who heads Houston's bid for a new team, believes  
his city has the edge in a poll of the divided group of owners. 
</P>
<P>
	``Clearly, you've got some owners who do not want to do  
anything, some owners who want to go to Houston ... Some who want 
to wait and see if something can be put together in Los Angeles,'' 
McNair said. 
</P>
<P>
	``You're going to have to get a coalition of at least two of  
those groups in order to come up with the 24 votes. So there has to 
be some type of compromise to resolve the issue.'' 
</P>
<P>
	He said the owners held a secret vote.  
</P>
<P>
	``Based upon what I've been told, I think we have more votes  
than anybody else in this beauty contest,'' McNair said. 
</P>
<P>
	But not enough.  
</P>
<P>
	San Diego Chargers owner Alex Spanos bemoaned what he sees as a  
lack of civic interest in Los Angeles, and appeared to be leaning 
toward Houston. He said he believes the odds are ``50-50'' for 
landing a new franchise. 
</P>
<P>
	``The city of Los Angeles hasn't shown it's ready. I'd like the  
city to get involved,'' Spanos said. ``Look at what Houston's 
done.'' 
</P>
<P>
	New York Giants owner Wellington Mara seemed to favor Los  
Angeles, noting ``all those TV sets.'' 
</P>
<P>
	The LA area is the nation's second-largest television market, to  
No. 11 for Houston. 
</P>
<P>
	Pittsburgh Steelers owner Dan Rooney sounded as if he's on the  
fence. 
</P>
<P>
	``We want to see LA with a team, believe me, we all do,'' he  
said. ``But there hasn't been much interest in Los Angeles.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Spanos shrugged off a question about the two proposed ownership  
groups in Los Angeles, one headed by Hollywood deal-maker Michael 
Ovitz and the other by developer Ed Roski and billionaire Eli 
Broad, turning back to what he considers a lack of government 
support for a new stadium. 
</P>
<P>
	Rooney said he had met Ovitz and Broad, adding, ``We heard them,  
what they want to do, and that's good. 
</P>
<P>
	``But where's the city?''  
</P>
<P>
	Commissioner Paul Tagliabue said earlier that he expects the  
owners to pick either Los Angeles or Houston this week, waiting 
until later to name an ownership group. 
</P>
<P>
	A decision on which city may be made Tuesday or Wednesday. No  
recommendation was made after Sunday's combined meeting of the 
finance and expansion committees. 
</P>
<P>
	A 32nd franchise, which would probably be the last added by the  
league for a long time, would be expected to begin play in 2002. 
</P>
<P>
	Dallas Cowboys owner Jerry Jones wants both cities to have a  
team, but feels there should be no rush about it. 
</P>
<P>
	``I think it's understandable to want a team in Los Angeles and  
a team in Houston. It's more a question of the timing and the 
owners and the stadium,'' Jones said. ``We will do the NFL in Los 
Angeles and in Houston. It's just a matter of how we get to that. 
</P>
<P>
	``I think LA is such a great market and we ultimately want a  
team there. But there are so many criteria to base it on, so it 
takes time to do that.'' 
</P>
<P>
	McNair already is contacting owners of existing teams about the  
possibility of moving to Texas, so both LA and Houston could wind 
up with teams. 
</P>
<P>
	Carmen Policy, president of the Cleveland Browns, had some  
concern about the status of Los Angeles' two plans for a stadium -- 
a new one that the Ovitz group would build in suburban Carson, or 
the remodeled Coliseum being pushed by Roski and Broad. 
</P>
<P>
	``I think there is a problem. From what I know, I get a sense  
the stadium plan is not solid in being implemented (in LA),'' 
Policy said. ``If there was a stadium plan like there is in 
Houston, there wouldn't be any doubt about Los Angeles.'' 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
