<DOCNO> APW19990314.0060 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-03-14 14:42:01 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> entertainment </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> 'Baywatch' Accused of Reneging Deal </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	BRISBANE, Australia (AP) -- A tourism official accused the TV  
series ``Baywatch'' on Sunday of reneging on a verbal agreement to 
film at least 22 episodes on Australia's Gold Coast. 
</P>
<P>
	Queensland state Tourism Minister Bob Gibbs said the producers  
simply used the negotiations with his government to squeeze 
concessions out of Hawaii, where the episodes are now expected to 
be made. 
</P>
<P>
	``It's disgraceful,'' said Gibbs on Sunday, a day after talks  
between state tourism officials and the show's producers failed to 
clinch the world's most watched television show for Australia. 
</P>
<P>
	In Hawaii, a spokeswoman for Gov. Ben Cayetano says a deal is  
close but not yet in place. 
</P>
<P>
	``It's close, but we haven't fully sealed the deal,''  
spokeswoman Kathleen Racuya-Markrich said Saturday night. 
</P>
<P>
	``Baywatch'' executives who attended the meetings in Queensland  
left their Gold Coast hotel early Sunday without commenting. Phone 
messages left at Baywatch Productions in Los Angeles on Sunday were 
not immediately returned. 
</P>
<P>
	Gibbs accused the producers of ``Baywatch'' of never having any  
intention of filming in Queensland, despite an in-principle 
``handshake'' agreement reached Feb. 26. 
</P>
<P>
	``Their coming to Queensland yesterday was nothing but a  
deceitful charade designed to panic Hawaii into signing a deal 
immediately,'' Gibbs said. 
</P>
<P>
	The TV show turned to Queensland after an initial plan to film  
at a beach north of Sydney fell through because of massive protests 
by locals who feared the filming would be an inconvenience and an 
invasion of privacy. 
</P>
<P>
	Hawaii lawmakers are now considering a state budget bill that  
includes $1.7 million for improvements intended to help attract 
``Baywatch'' to the islands. 
</P>
<P>
	About half of the money would go for improvements and equipment  
at the city's Haleiwa Recreational Center and half for improvements 
at the Hawaii Film Studio at Diamond Head. 
</P>
<P>
	An official familiar with the negotiations said ``Baywatch''  
producers said they need a water tank for underwater shots. It's 
not clear if money for the tank is part of the budget money. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
