<CATEGORY> usa </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> AP Top News at 7 p.m. EST  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	U.S. Prison Population Has Doubled  
</P>
<P>
	WASHINGTON (AP) -- The number of adult Americans in prison has  
more than doubled since 1985, and the U.S. may soon surpass Russia 
as the country with the highest rate of incarceration. The Justice 
Department said today that at mid-1998, jails and prisons held an 
estimated 1.8 million people, according to a Bureau of Justice 
Statistics report. At the end of 1985, the figure was 744,208. 
Viewed another way, there were 668 inmates for every 100,000 U.S. 
residents as of June 1998, compared with 313 inmates per 100,000 
people in 1985. 

</P>
<P>
	White House Defends Spy Response  
</P>
<P>
	WASHINGTON (AP) -- While admitting that the Chinese gained from  
nuclear technology allegedly stolen from a Los Alamos lab, Clinton 
administration officials say the government responded decisively to 
the situation. Republicans disagreed and pressed for a review of 
U.S. policy toward China. ``This is a very dangerous situation 
involving international espionage that directly threatens the 
security of all Americans,'' said Sen. John McCain, a GOP 
presidential hopeful. National security advisor Sandy Berger said 
the Chinese did benefit from the leak in the 1980s. But, ``I think 
we moved swiftly and I think we continue to impose on China the 
strictest controls,'' he told NBC. 

</P>
<P>
	Study Links Smoking, Adult Crime  
</P>
<P>
	CHICAGO (AP) -- Researchers say that babies whose mothers smoke  
are at a higher risk of growing up to be criminals. A study 
published in this month's Archives of General Psychiatry is the 
first to examine the relationship between mothers who smoke and 
their children's adult behavior. While stopping short of saying 
that babies whose mothers smoked while pregnant will become 
criminals, researchers say their findings are significant. The 
researchers based their findings on data for 4,169 males born in 
Copenhagen, Denmark, between September 1959 and December 1961 and 
studied the men's arrest histories at age 34. 

</P>
<P>
	Report: Congolese Rebels Kill 100  
</P>
<P>
	KIGALI, Rwanda (AP) -- More than 100 villagers in southeastern  
Congo were killed by Congolese rebels, the Italian Missionary 
Service News Agency reported today. The rebels, fighting to oust 
Congolese President Laurent Kabila, apparently killed the villagers 
in retaliation for an attack by a pro-government militia, the 
report said. There was no independent confirmation of the report, 
and no rebel officials in the central African nation were readily 
available for comment. 

</P>
<P>
	Netanyahu Warns Palestinians  
</P>
<P>
	BEIT SHEMESH, Israel (AP) -- Israel will respond ``very  
forcefully'' if Palestinians declare statehood in May and claim 
Jerusalem as the capital. That is what Prime Minister Benjamin 
Netanyahu said today in a campaign speech before high school 
students. ``If you violate the agreement and unilaterally declare a 
Palestinian state with Jerusalem as its capital, know that on May 
5, we will respond very forcefully,'' Netanyahu said. ``It won't be 
good for the Palestinians, and it won't be good for peace.'' 

</P>
<P>
	U.N.: Afghanistan Coalition Agreed  
</P>
<P>
	ASHGABAT, Turkmenistan (AP) -- Warring factions in Afghanistan  
have preliminarily agreed to a coalition government, a move that 
could mean an end to decades of fighting that has killed tens of 
thousands of people. The agreement could enable the creation of a 
coalition government to include all of the country's political 
forces, U.N. mediators said today. The deal was reached between 
Afghanistan's ruling Taliban Islamic movement and its main foe, the 
northern opposition, the U.N. Special Mission to Afghanistan said. 

</P>
<P>
	Ford Fined in Recall Settlement  
</P>
<P>
	WASHINGTON (AP) -- Ford Motor Co. has agreed to pay a civil fine  
of $425,000 in a settlement with the federal government for failing 
to recall vehicles promptly and withholding information during a 
safety agency's investigations into fires in Ford cars and light 
trucks. National Highway Traffic Safety Administration officials 
said Ford was too slow in recalling and fixing 8.6 million vehicles 
in 1996. The safety agency also said Ford failed to provide 
complete and accurate information in four investigations into fires 
in Ford vehicles between 1992 and 1996. 

</P>
<P>
	Miami of Ohio, SW Mo. St. Advance  
</P>
<P>
	NEW ORLEANS (AP) -- Miami of Ohio beat Utah 66-58 today, earning  
the team's first trip to the NCAA tournament's round of 16, and 
continuing a string of upsets in this year's tournament. Wally 
Szczerbiak, who scored 43 points against Washington in the first 
round, scored 24 points to lead the Ohio club. Meanwhile, Southwest 
Missouri State got a big 81-51 win over Tennessee, also earning the 
team's first trip to the Sweet 16. 

</P>
<P>
	AP NewsBrief by BRADLEY BROOKS  



</P>
</TEXT>
