<DATE_TIME> 1999-03-14 16:32:49 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> sports </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Swingley Has Big Lead in Iditarod </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	ANCHORAGE, Alaska (AP) -- Doug Swingley reached the Bering Sea  
coast Sunday morning and is threatening to make the 27th Iditarod 
Trail Sled Dog Race one of the most lopsided ever. 
</P>
<P>
	Swingley, of Lincoln, Mont., had at least a nine-hour lead over  
Martin Buser. Most years, the winner usually crosses the finish 
line no more than a few hours ahead of the nearest pursuer. 
</P>
<P>
	Swingley reached Unalakleet at 10:08 a.m. local time, and said  
he expected to rest for at least eight hours before heading north 
toward Shaktoolik. 
</P>
<P>
	He earned $2,500 in gold for getting to the coast first.  
</P>
<P>
	Buser, of Big Lake, left the Kaltag checkpoint, 90 miles from  
Unalakleet, at 9:19 a.m. Even if the nine dogs he has left perform 
flawlessly, it still should take Buser nine hours to reach 
Unalakleet. 
</P>
<P>
	Swingley hold the Iditarod course record of nine days, two hours  
for the 1,100-mile race from Anchorage to Nome. 
</P>
<P>
	On Sunday he appeared to be about four hours off that 1995  
record pace. It's the only time he has won the Iditarod. Buser is a 
three-time champion. 
</P>
<P>
	Behind Buser, five-time winner Rick Swenson of Two Rivers and  
three-time winner Jeff King of Denali Park were resting in Kaltag. 
Eleven more mushers were headed there. 
</P>
<P>
	From Unalakleet, Swingley has 229 miles to go before he reaches  
the finish line. 
</P>
<P>
	The Montanan pulled into Unalakleet with 13 dogs in harness but  
told race officials he planed to drop one dog there. He also 
confessed to some fatigue. 
</P>
<P>
	``The trail just beats on you,'' Swingley told radio station  
KNOM. ``I've been sleeping too much on my sled. I think I need a 
long break ... I've had about 700 catnaps in the past hundred 
miles.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Forty-nine teams were still on the trail Sunday, down from 56  
who started the race a week ago. 
</P>
<P>
	While Swingley could dream of sleeping in a warm bed by Tuesday,  
the back of the pack might have at least six more days of mushing 
ahead of it. 
</P>
<P>
	Bringing up the rear was Shane Goosen, a rookie from Wasilla. He  
was headed for Shageluk on Sunday, about 500 miles from Nome. 
</P>
<P>
	The winner gets $54,000 from the $450,000 purse. Prize money is  
paid to the first 20 finishers. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW19990314.0063 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-03-14 18:21:49 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> sports </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> NCAA East Regional Notebook </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	BOSTON (AP) -- Underdog Purdue made the round of 16 and even one  
of its best players is a bit surprised. 
</P>
<P>
	Brian Cardinal led the 10th-seeded Boilermakers with 20 points  
and four steals in Sunday's 73-63 win over second-seeded Miami. 
That came two days after they beat Texas 58-54. Not bad for a team 
that lost five of its previous six games and was worried it might 
not even get into the tournament. 
</P>
<P>
	Now the Boilermakers are headed for the Meadowlands in East  
Rutherford, N.J., where they'll play sixth-seeded Temple on Friday. 
</P>
<P>
	After Sunday's win, Cardinal was asked what he would have said  
if someone told him two weeks ago he would be going there. 
</P>
<P>
	``I'd want to know where I was sitting in the stands because I  
didn't think we would get there,'' he said. 
</P>
<P>
                             	------	 
</P>
<P>
	BRIGHTER DAYS:@ Despite the loss, Miami enjoyed an outstanding  
season in which it went 23-7, won its first NCAA tournament game 
ever and was ranked 10th nationally. 
</P>
<P>
	That's a decent foundation for a team that didn't have a  
basketball program from 1971 through 1985. 
</P>
<P>
	``We made tremendous progress and we're a good basketball  
team,'' coach Leonard Hamilton said. ``This is probably the first 
night where we had this empty feeling and went out and felt we 
didn't play our best.'' 
</P>
<P>
	The only key senior the Hurricanes lose is forward Tim James,  
the Big East co-player of the year. 
</P>
<P>
	``I just told the guys to keep their heads up,'' James said.  
</P>
<P>
	He was bothered my back problems during the tournament.  
</P>
<P>
	``It would be unprofessional for me to use it as an excuse,''  
Hamilton said, ``but to say that he was 100 percent is to say I'm 
not being honest.'' 
</P>
<P>
                             	------	 
</P>
<P>
	STEALING SANCHEZ:@ Temple's Pepe Sanchez made a big mark in the  
box score for his second straight game. 
</P>
<P>
	In Friday's opening 61-54 win over Kent, he had some eye-popping  
numbers for a point guard -- 40 minutes, nine assists and no steals. 
And in Sunday's 64-54 win over Cincinnati, he led the team with 
seven rebounds and four steals. 
</P>
<P>
	``When Pepe's not in the game everything's wrong,'' Temple coach  
John Chaney said. ``When you find a point guard, you want to build 
your program around that.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Sanchez set the school single-season record with 94 steals, one  
more than he had last year. And the team had nine steals, setting a 
single-season record of 327. The old mark was 321 set last year. 
</P>
<P>
                             	------	 
</P>
<P>
	MORE NUMBERS:@ The Purdue-Miami game produced some strange  
statistics. Miami, which lost, took 76 shots. Purdue tried only 38. 
Miami also had a 45-29 rebounding advantage. 
</P>
<P>
	So why didn't Miami win?  
</P>
<P>
	Purdue made 24-of-37 free throws, while Miami went 12-for-15  
from the line. In the last seven minutes, all the Boilermakers 
points came on free throws as they went 19-for-28. 
</P>
<P>
                             	------	 
</P>
<P>
	SMALL CONSOLATION:@ Cincinnati was eliminated in the second  
round for the third straight year, but coach Bob Huggins wasn't 
completely disappointed. 
</P>
<P>
	They went into the tournament ranked 11th in the nation and  
finished with a 27-6 record as they made their eighth straight 
appearance in the NCAA tournament. 
</P>
<P>
	Huggins denies his team is an underachiever.  
</P>
<P>
	``I don't read the papers so I don't worry about that,'' he  
said. ``A lot of teams would like to be like us.'' 
</P>
</TEXT>
