<CATEGORY> political </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Report: N.J. Gov. To Run for Senate </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	TRENTON, N.J. (AP) -- Gov. Christie Whitman has decided to run  
for U.S. Senate in 2000, according to a newspaper report Sunday. 
</P>
<P>
	Citing unnamed Republican sources, The Trentonian reported that  
Whitman will seek the GOP's nomination for the seat being vacated 
by retiring Democrat Frank Lautenberg. 
</P>
<P>
	Whitman spokesman Peter McDonough denied that the governor has  
made definite plans. 
</P>
<P>
	McDonough said Whitman's decision will depend on how quickly she  
can reach the three main objectives of her second term: a 
billion-dollar property tax rebate program, a million acres of 
open-space preservation and whole-school reform. 
</P>
<P>
	``The question now is whether or not she could get these  
accomplished before she would have to depart for Washington should 
she run'' for Senate, McDonough said. 
</P>
<P>
	McDonough said Whitman will announce her intentions within a few  
weeks after her trip to South America, where she is heading a 
10-day New Jersey trade mission. 
</P>
<P>
	Lautenberg unexpectedly announced his retirement last month.  
Republican leaders in New Jersey and nationwide have urged Whitman 
to run for the seat. 
</P>
<P>
	Whitman's decision may set up a rematch with former Gov. Jim  
Florio, a Democrat whom Whitman unseated in 1993. Florio is 
expected to seek the Democratic nomination to succeed Lautenberg. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW19990314.0065 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-03-14 13:21:39 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> sports </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Sheffield Talking Retirement </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	VERO BEACH, Fla. (AP) -- Los Angeles Dodgers outfielder Gary  
Sheffield, bothered by a sore shoulder, a position change and the 
team dress policy, is talking about possible retirement. 
</P>
<P>
	``To be honest with you, if I still didn't have five years left  
(on his contract), and if not for the trade, I would retire right 
now,'' Sheffield told the Los Angeles Times on Sunday, referring to 
the seven-player deal last May that sent catcher Mike Piazza to the 
Florida Marlins. 
</P>
<P>
	Piazza later went to the New York Mets, and Sheffield is the  
lone player from the trade still with the Dodgers. 
</P>
<P>
	``Just the grind of everything, every day, has been (wearing) on  
me, and you can only take but so much,'' Sheffield said. ``But 
you're supposed to honor things that you agree to, and that's what 
I'm trying to do, but it's hard.'' 
</P>
<P>
	The 30-year-old outfielder is in the second year of a six-year,  
$61 million contract. He underwent surgery on the shoulder to 
repair tendon damage in the off-season. 
</P>
<P>
	Sheffield, shifted from right to left field this year, began  
feeling increased pain in his right shoulder after a game Friday in 
which he went hitless in three at-bats. He received a cortisone 
shot in the shoulder Saturday. 
</P>
<P>
	Sheffield said team medical personnel told him the pain is  
unrelated to his recent surgery. He hopes to return to action soon, 
but expressed concern that his rehabilitation is not going well. 
</P>
<P>
	When told of Sheffield's comments, Dodger general manager Kevin  
Malone downplayed it, saying: ``It's spring training, and you have 
some good days and some bad days. 
</P>
<P>
	``I think Gary is just going through a frustrating time over his  
shoulder not being where he wants it to be right now. I spent time 
with Gary (on Friday) and he said his shoulder felt a lot better. 
We walked together and talked together, and he never brought this 
up to me or Davey (Dodgers manager Davey Johnson).'' 
</P>
<P>
	In an interview early this month, Sheffield said shifting  
positions didn't bother him -- even though he spent most of his 
11-year major league career in right field. Raul Mondesi had moved 
from right to center field when Sheffield joined the team, and 
Mondesi went back to right this spring after the Dodgers acquired 
Devon White to play center. 
</P>
<P>
	He has apparently changed his mind.  
</P>
<P>
	``Obviously, I'm not comfortable,'' Sheffield said. ``I'm fine  
with whatever makes Mondy happy because we need Mondy to be happy, 
and I'm a team player. Davey says I'm too hard on myself, that I'm 
too much of a perfectionist, but I just don't want to be 
embarrassed out there. If I'm embarrassed I can't do it, and I'll 
just say I can't do it.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Also, Sheffield was annoyed by the team's decision to again  
enforce dress codes and personal-grooming guidelines. They were 
relaxed last season to accommodate Sheffield after the trade. 
</P>
<P>
	``I'm tired of every decision always being around me,''  
Sheffield said. ``I just want to wear my facial hair and earrings 
and just play the game.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Sheffield was not singled out, Malone said: ``Those are Dodger  
rules that we're just enforcing, they have nothing to do with any 
individual in particular.'' 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW19990314.0066 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-03-14 10:31:20 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
