<HEADLINE> NCAA East Regional Notebook </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	CHARLOTTE, N.C. (AP) -- An expected showdown between two of the  
country's best big men, Duke's Elton Brand and Tulsa's Michael 
Ruffin, fizzled immediately in Sunday's East Regional second-round 
game. 
</P>
<P>
	Tulsa went down low to Ruffin on its first possession. His shot  
was blocked by Brand. 
</P>
<P>
	On the other end, Brand outdueled Ruffin for a rebound and put  
up a follow shot for Duke's first basket. 
</P>
<P>
	The trend continued on the Golden Hurricane's next possession,  
when Ruffin was called for an offensive foul, his first of three in 
the opening half. 
</P>
<P>
	By the time the game ended, Brand had 17 points and six  
rebounds, and Duke had a 97-56 victory. Ruffin didn't score but had 
eight rebounds and three blocks. 
</P>
<P>
	Alas, even if Ruffin's basketball career doesn't pan out, he  
appears to have a good chance of professional success. He has a 
3.77 grade-point average in chemical engineering. 
</P>
<P>
                             	------	 
</P>
<P>
	 *BACK OFF: Southwest Missouri State coach Steve Alford wasn't  
real interested in being interviewed live on television at the end 
of the first half of the Bears' game against Tennessee. 
</P>
<P>
	A network crew swooped in on Alford as the teams went off the  
floor and began conducting an interview, apparently oblivious to 
the fact that Alford wasn't paying attention. With a microphone 
planted in his face, he kept lobbying the officials to give his 
team credit for a 3-point shot at the buzzer instead of a 
two-pointer, as the scoreboard originally showed. 
</P>
<P>
	Alford won his case -- then gave the network a brief interview.  
</P>
<P>
                             	------	 
</P>
<P>
	 *SUNDAYS IN CHARLOTTE: Playing on Sunday afternoons at the  
Charlotte Coliseum apparently agrees with Duke point guard William 
Avery. 
</P>
<P>
	Avery had 19 points, six rebounds and two assists Sunday, when  
he played just 28 minutes. 
</P>
<P>
	One week earlier, in the Atlantic Coast Conference title game on  
the same floor, Avery had 29 points, five assists and four steals 
to lead the top-ranked Blue Devils to a 96-73 victory over North 
Carolina. 
</P>
<P>
                             	------	 
</P>
<P>
	 *BEEN THERE, DONE THAT: Tennessee' 81-51 loss to Southwest  
Missouri State marked the second consecutive year that the Vols 
were ousted from the NCAA tournament by a member of the Missouri 
Valley Conference. 
</P>
<P>
	Illinois State eliminated Tennessee in the opening round last  
year. 
</P>
<P>
	For the record, Tennessee has an all-time record of 2-8 against  
MVC schools. Southwest Missouri State is 6-17 against Southeastern 
Conference opponents. 
</P>
<P>
                             	------	 
</P>
<P>
	 *MOTIVATION: Duke coach Mike Krzyzewski had a few choice,  
unprintable words for his players when they came to the bench 
during the game's first television timeout and the Blue Devils up 
9-8. 
</P>
<P>
	Krzyzewski pointedly asked his players if they were saving  
themselves for something. 
</P>
<P>
	The chat worked.  
</P>
<P>
	When the Devils came to the bench for the second television  
timeout, they were up 22-8, putting them well on their way to 
victory and a spot in the East Regional semifinals in East 
Rutherford, N.J. 
</P>
<P>
                             	------	 
</P>
<P>
	 *FAMILY AFFAIR: After Alford finished his postgame interviews in  
the media area, he returned to the Charlotte Coliseum floor to meet 
his family. 
</P>
<P>
	``Let's go to New Jersey,'' he yelled as his wife, Tanya, and  
two sons, Bryce and Kory, waited to greet him near the courtside 
press table. 
</P>
<P>
	Before they left the coliseum, however, the Alfords had a  
Southwest Missouri State athletic department official take their 
picture as they posed in front of a NCAA tournament banner at the 
scorer's table. 
</P>
<P>
                             	------	 
</P>
<P>
	 *FAMILIARITY: Sunday's game was not the only recent meeting  
between Duke and Tulsa. 
</P>
<P>
	The two schools played at Madison Square Garden in the  
semifinals of the 1996 preseason National Invitation Tournament. 
The Blue Devils won 72-67. 
</P>
<P>
                             	------	 
</P>
<P>
	 *DOSE OF REALITY: One enterprising Southwest Missouri State fan  
showed up for Sunday's game with a two-sided cardboard sign. 
</P>
<P>
	The front said: ``WE WANT DUKE.''  
</P>
<P>
	The back said: ``TO LET US WIN.''  
</P>
