<CATEGORY> sports </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> NCAA Midwest Regional Notebook </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	MILWAUKEE (AP) -- The Oklahoma Sooners are in the round of 16  
because they know how to make up for the lack of an inside game: 
get the sharpshooters open. 
</P>
<P>
	After all, they're even naming babies after this style.  
</P>
<P>
	``Ray Lopes has been with me for seven years,'' coach Kelvin  
Sampson said Sunday. ``His wife just had a baby. They named it 
Marcus Ray. We made 10 3s against Arizona and they changed the name 
to Trey Alexander. That tells you about our program.'' 
</P>
<P>
	So does the 13 3s the Sooners made Sunday -- a school postseason  
record -- in their 85-72 upset of North Carolina-Charlotte that 
propelled them to the round of 16 for the first time in a decade. 
</P>
<P>
	On Sunday, the Sooners made up for their lack of an inside game  
by continually isolating their jumpshooters on the left side and 
concentrating their ball movement to the right. 
</P>
<P>
	When the sole defender moved to help guard the penetrater or  
double the post, his man was left with wide-open long-range looks. 
</P>
<P>
	``That's what good teams do, they find the open guy,'' said  
senior Eric Martin, who scored all 18 of his points on 3s. 
</P>
<P>
	``We didn't want our player to leave the passer if he was a  
shooter and twice that happened,'' 49ers coach Bobby Lutz said. 
``We left Martin to double in the post and he hit the shots.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Charlotte hit only 5 of 29 shots in the first half.  
</P>
<P>
	``We knew they were good shooters and we left them a little too  
open, obviously,'' Lutz said. 
</P>
<P>
	``Coach told us that they're very similar to us and you can't  
just run plays for 40 minutes against a hard-nosed defensive 
team,'' Martin said. ``You've just got to make plays on your own. 
We made plays and my teammates found me in the open and I knocked 
down the shots.'' 
</P>
<P>
                             	------	 
</P>
<P>
	 *QUID PRO QUO:* Michigan State coach Tom Izzo figures the  
Spartans' next opponent, Oklahoma, owes him a favor when they meet 
in St. Louis in the Midwest Regional semifinal round. 
</P>
<P>
	Or at least a thank you note from Sooners coach Kelvin Sampson.  
</P>
<P>
	By virtue of their 13th seed, the Sooners were the last at-large  
team to make the NCAA tournament. The selection committee said that 
had Illinois beaten Michigan State in the Big Ten title game, the 
Illini would have become the eighth Big Ten team to make it. 
</P>
<P>
	That would have bumped out the Sooners despite their  
second-place finish in the Big 12. 
</P>
<P>
	Izzo didn't want to comment on the matchup with the Sooners.  
</P>
<P>
	``Just that Kelvin Sampson's an old Michigan State guy,'' Izzo  
said. ``And No. 2, you know, I talked to Jud Heathcote early and he 
said he called Kelvin and thanks to our win over Illinois might 
have got them in. 
</P>
<P>
	``So I hope he repays the favor.''  
</P>
<P>
                             	------	 
</P>
<P>
	 *OUCH!* Michigan State guard Charlie Bell may have had a  
sprained ankle, but he didn't play like it. 
</P>
<P>
	Bell, who had a brace and heavy tape on his left ankle, came off  
the bench for 14 minutes and scored five points Sunday in Michigan 
State's 74-66 victory over Mississippi. He also had one assist. 
</P>
<P>
	Bell's ankle has been a problem all season, and he aggravated it  
in Friday night's rout of Mount St. Mary's. 
</P>
<P>
                             	------	 
</P>
<P>
	 *MUGSY BOGUES II?* Mississippi guard Jason Harrison is listed at  
5-foot-5. In platform sneakers, maybe. 
</P>
<P>
	But what the diminutive guard lacks in size, he makes up for in  
hustle and heart. 
</P>
<P>
	Harrison was the sparkplug for the Rebels in the first and  
second rounds of the Midwest Regional. Against Michigan State, he 
scored seven points, including a big 3-pointer over All-American 
Mateen Cleaves that put the Rebels up 59-56 in the closing minutes. 
</P>
<P>
	``He was tough,'' Cleaves said. ``I had played against (George  
Washington's) Shante Rogers and (former Eastern Michigan point 
guard) Earl Boykins, and he ranks up there with those guys. He's 
gonna be tough. He plays real good defense and the thing I like 
about him is he's a competitor.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Though Harrison was Arkansas' Mr. Basketball last year and led  
his Little Rock Parkview High School to the Arkansas 4A title, he 
said he wasn't recruited by any Division I schools. He signed with 
Henderson State, a Division II school, but decided to follow Eric 
Bozeman when Bozeman left Henderson State to join Rod Barnes' 
staff. 
</P>
<P>
	Barnes said he wasn't turned off by Harrison's size at all.  
</P>
<P>
	``If you can play this game, you can play it,'' Barnes said. ``I  
think people overrate size and all that kind of stuff. The bottom 
line is you've got to put the ball in the basket and you've got to 
stop the other team. 
</P>
<P>
	``Size and height and all that stuff can help, but I'm one who  
believes that hard work and a big heart and a passion for whatever 
you do can help you be successful, and Jason Harrison is a prime 
example of that.'' 
</P>
</TEXT>
