<HEADLINE> AP Top News at 9 a.m. EST  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	Afghanistan Coalition Rule Crafted  
</P>
<P>
	ASHGABAT, Turkmenistan (AP) -- The warring factions in  
Afghanistan have agreed in principle on the creation of a coalition 
government to include all of the country's political forces, U.N. 
mediators said today. The agreement, the first such deal between 
the factions, could mean an end to two decades of fighting that has 
killed tens of thousands of people and destroyed vast areas of the 
country, including the capital of Kabul. The deal was reached 
between Afghanistan's ruling Taliban Islamic movement and its main 
foe, the northern opposition, the U.N. Special Mission to 
Afghanistan said in a statement. 

</P>
<P>
	U.S. Planes Attack Iraq Sites  
</P>
<P>
	ANKARA, Turkey (AP) -- U.S. fighter planes bombed several Iraqi  
air defense sites when they came under fire during routine 
enforcement of the northern ``no-fly'' zone today, a U.S. military 
official said. In response to Iraqi fire, Air Force F-15E Strike 
Eagles dropped bombs on several anti-aircraft artillery sites 
northwest and west of the city of Mosul, 250 miles north of 
Baghdad, said Capt. Manning Brown, a spokesman for the Operation 
Northern Watch based in southern Incirlik Air Base. ``All coalition 
aircraft departed the area safely,'' Brown said. 

</P>
<P>
	Kosovo Peace Plan May Adavnce  
</P>
<P>
	PRISTINA, Yugoslavia (AP) -- Ethnic Albanian delegates have said  
they were are prepared to sign a U.S.-backed Kosovo peace plan. 
Departing for peace talks in France, delegates said they would sign 
if the Serb-led government backs down on its opposition to allowing 
NATO troops to enforce it. Meanwhile, there was no letup in the 
fighting between government forces and ethnic Albanian rebels in 
the province in southern Serbia. Three bombs went off in two 
government-controlled cities, killing at least six people. 

</P>
<P>
	U.K., U.S. Probing Insurance Scam  
</P>
<P>
	LONDON (AP) -- Britain and the United States are investigating  
whether Lloyd's of London insurance companies are being used by 
American crime syndicates as a cover for scams that could cost 
hundreds of millions of dollars in lost claims, The Sunday Times 
reported. Several British firms have been raided during the 
four-month investigation, Lloyd's spokesman Nick Doak confirmed. 
The newspaper said the fraud is thought to involve bogus insurance 
companies set up by American crime syndicates registered offshore 
in the Caribbean. 

</P>
<P>
	Police Misconduct Concerns Clinton  
</P>
<P>
	LITTLE ROCK, Ark. (AP) -- Allegations of wrongdoing by police are  
on President Clinton's mind this weekend. In a radio speech 
yesterday, Clinton expressed concern that recent charges of police 
misconduct could undermine the fight against crime. He also 
proposed improved training and other steps to restore the ``bonds 
of trust'' between the public and law enforcement. Recent 
questionable shootings by police that took the lives of young 
blacks in New York, Pittsburgh and Riverside, Calif., have revived 
debate about how officers handle confrontations with minorities. 

</P>
<P>
	Plains, Midwest Hit With Snow Storm  
</P>
<P>
	NEW YORK (AP) -- Snow fell heavily in the central Plains and the  
Midwest yesterday, with up to 14 inches blanketing western Kansas 
and a line of thunderstorms swept from eastern Texas through 
Louisiana into Mississippi, Alabama and eastern Tennessee. The 
National Weather Service issued a tornado watch for sections of 
Louisiana, Mississippi, Alabama and extreme northwestern Florida. 

</P>
<P>
	Abortion Clinic Rocked by Bomb  
</P>
<P>
	ASHEVILLE, N.C. (AP) -- A bomb planted outside an abortion clinic  
exploded yesterday, causing no injuries and little damage because 
it detonated only partially. The clinic, less than 75 miles from 
the mountainous area where serial bombing suspect Eric Rudolph is 
believed to be hiding, received no advance warning of the bomb. 
When asked about a possible link between the explosion and Rudolph, 
FBI spokeswoman Joanne Morley said: ``At this stage, we don't 
discount anything.'' 

</P>
<P>
	March Madness Moves On  
</P>
<P>
	SEATTLE (AP) -- Stanford, which lost to Kentucky in the national  
semifinals last year, was the last of four Pac-10 teams to be 
eliminated from this year's tournament, losing yesterday. Arizona, 
Washington and UCLA all lost in the first round. Meanwhile, 
Connecticut scored the first 17 points of the game and cruised into 
the round of 16. 

</P>
<P>
	Heavyweight Draw Angers Fans  
</P>
<P>
	NEW YORK (AP) -- Evander Holyfield escaped with a loudly booed  
draw against Lennox Lewis last night at Madison Square Garden as 
the 33-year-old Briton seemed to dominate the 12-round bout for the 
undisputed heavyweight championship. According to a punch count, 
Lewis landed 348 of 613 punches for a connection rate of 57 
percent. Holyfield connected on 130 of 385 punches, or 34 percent. 

</P>
<P>
	AP NewsBrief by DAVID GOODMAN  
</P>
</TEXT>
