<CATEGORY> financial </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Too Many Projects, Not Enough Steel </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	PITTSBURGH (AP) -- A creaky 90-year-old bridge in northwestern  
Pennsylvania has nearly everything it needs to be replaced this 
year: enough federal dollars, an eager contractor and plenty of 
American-made raw steel. 
</P>
<P>
	But overloaded fabricators can't turn that steel into girders  
fast enough. 
</P>
<P>
	Massive road and bridge projects being funded with money from  
the 1998 Federal Highway Act -- including the Kennerdell Bridge 
project in Pennsylvania's Venango County -- have suddenly created a 
huge demand for fabricated steel. 
</P>
<P>
	``What you've got is huge projects hitting at the same time and  
going through major fabricators,'' said Steve Bussanmas, senior 
vice president of sales and marketing for High Steel Structures in 
Lancaster, which supplies fabricated steel to contractors 
nationwide. ``It's causing quite a backlog.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Salt Lake City is using thousands of tons of fabricated steel to  
build more than 130 bridges to prepare for the 2002 Winter Olympic 
Games. Boston is constructing the multibillion-dollar ``Big Dig,'' 
a new underground central artery to alleviate traffic congestion. 
</P>
<P>
	The federal highway bill increased demand almost exponentially.  
High Steel hired more workers last year and this year, and the mill 
operates seven days a week, including around the clock on week 
days. 
</P>
<P>
	Some fabricators, including Stupp Brothers Bridge and Iron Co.  
in St. Louis, are opening new plants to further increase output. 
</P>
<P>
	But most fabricators want to know if the current boom will  
deflate before they hire more permanent employees or open more 
plants, said Bob Nickerson, a Baltimore engineer and steel industry 
consultant studying reasons for the sudden demand. 
</P>
<P>
	``Fabricators don't want to build a new plant and find that  
owners stop ordering steel next year,'' he said. ``We need to make 
sure our capacity problem is not just a short-term peak issue.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Nickerson said he would report his findings to the American  
Institute of Steel Construction in Chicago this month. That group 
is the steel fabrication industry's major national professional 
organization. 
</P>
<P>
	That ``transient mentality'' is what leaves the construction  
industry scrambling when facing a sudden boom, said Robert 
Morehead, spokesman for the National Center for Construction 
Education and Research in Gainesville, Fla. 
</P>
<P>
	``When the economy is going nuts like it is now, they say they  
need to hire more people, and lose business while they take time to 
train them,'' Morehead said. 
</P>
<P>
	``Then when the economy slows down, they scale back and stop  
training. Five years from now when the economy takes off again, 
they will have the same situation, and worse,'' he said. 
</P>
<P>
	Morehead said the industry needs to hire and train when business  
is slow to be ready when it booms. Current demands will decrease, 
particularly when the Boston project is completed, but business 
will pick up again. 
</P>
<P>
	In the meantime, state governments are trying to find steel, or  
trying to make do with their crumbling infrastructure while they 
wait for steel to arrive. 
</P>
<P>
	The Pennsylvania Department of Transportation had planned to  
replace the aging, one-lane Kennerdell Bridge, about 55 miles north 
of Pittsburgh, this year. The well-traveled bridge crosses the 
Allegheny River. 
</P>
<P>
	Mark Rinker, the contractor awarded the $7 million bid for the  
bridge, said he's turned to fabricators he hasn't used before in 
hopes of getting the steel. All told him they needed 10 months to a 
year to supply the 750 tons of girders. The project had to be 
postponed until spring 2000. 
</P>
<P>
	So, PennDOT will patch up the bridge and maintain its five-ton  
weight limit. 
</P>
<P>
	Other states have found ways to avoid construction delays. The  
New York Department of Transportation altered contract schedules 
and shortened review time so it did not have to put off any road 
and bridge projects this year, department spokesman Michael 
Fleischer said. 
</P>
<P>
	Not so in Pennsylvania, though, where Venango County residents  
who use the bridge every day sigh at the thought of living with it 
another year. 
</P>
<P>
	``People who use it wish it would hurry up and be replaced,''  
said William Bell, secretary for Rockland Township in Kennerdell. 
``No one is nervous about using it, but we need a new bridge.'' 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
