<CATEGORY> sports </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Royals Off to Roaring Spring Start </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	HAINES CITY, Fla. (AP) -- Yeah, it's only spring training. So  
what? 
</P>
<P>
	The 10-1 Royals are still the winningest team in the Grapefruit  
League, hitting, pitching and playing defense just like the 
high-priced contenders they aren't supposed to be. 
</P>
<P>
	And that's an encouraging relief to a collection of unproven  
young players who pitched camp just two weeks ago amid dire 
predictions of sorrow and woe. 
</P>
<P>
	``I understand some people are saying this team's going to lose  
100 games.'' said closer Jeff Montgomery, one of the few veterans 
on a club that won only 72 games last year and then lost its top 
two run-producers and No. 1 starter. 
</P>
<P>
	``Well, we all understand that when the regular season starts,  
established teams and established players will kick it up a notch. 
But winning is a byproduct of executing. And in several games, I've 
seen us do things that other clubs didn't do as well, which 
resulted in us winning.'' 
</P>
<P>
	After split squad games with Detroit and Houston were rained out  
Sunday, the Royals were averaging 6.4 runs and 11.5 hits per game 
and were second among AL teams with a .335 batting average. They 
were first with a .529 slugging percentage and among the leaders 
with 13 home runs, 26 doubles and 126 hits. 
</P>
<P>
	Their pitchers had given up 33 earned runs in 99 innings for a  
league-best ERA of 3.00. 
</P>
<P>
	They've beaten Roger Clemens and cuffed Greg Maddux around. Yes,  
three of their wins came against the woeful Florida Marlins. But 
they've also wracked up two wins each over the Yankees and Indians 
and bested the Dodgers, Cardinals (minus Mark McGwire) and Braves. 
</P>
<P>
	``The one thing about winning is that it's contagious,'' said  
catcher Sal Fasano. ``You get in the habit of finding a way to win. 
The best thing that could happen to a young team is to prove to 
them that we can find a way to beat good teams.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Until a couple of days ago, camp was bulging with a team-record  
69 players. But instead of chaos, order has reigned. Using all six 
fields at their Baseball City complex, manager Tony Muser and his 
staff are running a highly organized operation where everybody gets 
plenty of work and not a minute is wasted. 
</P>
<P>
	``It's been very efficient from the first day,'' said outfielder  
Johnny Damon. ``Nobody stands around waiting for somebody to tell 
them where to go. Everything goes off on schedule.'' 
</P>
<P>
	The Royals have about six major league jobs open, which may  
account as much as anything for all these wins. With so many jobs 
to be won, young players eager for a shot at the majors are staying 
focused and competing as hard as they can. 
</P>
<P>
	``There are a lot of guys here with a lot to prove,'' said  
general manager Herk Robinson. ``There are a lot of openings on 
this club and players are going to have to do things correctly to 
stay.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Muser, starting his second full year as manager, says it's the  
most competitive camp he's ever been involved with. 
</P>
<P>
	``Guys are busting their butt for jobs. They know they're being  
pressed by others and that everything they do matters,'' he said. 
</P>
<P>
	Nevertheless, being 10-1 is a lot better than being 1-10,  
especially for a team that all the experts are saying won't have a 
chance of competing. 
</P>
<P>
	And who knows? If these young players keep on winning, maybe the  
club will change its mind about unloading the few high-priced 
veterans still left, such as former ace right-hander Kevin Appier 
and first baseman Jeff King. 
</P>
<P>
	``I hope the people (in the front office) are watching what's  
happening and starting to think twice,'' said Montgomery. ``Let's 
hold on to Appier and see what happens with this season. It might 
be a lot more interesting than they even thought it would be.'' 
</P>
<P>
	``We've said all along we'll do what's in the best interests of  
the club,'' said Robinson. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
