<CATEGORY> financial </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> New Strain of Catfish Developed / Farm Scene  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	DEMOPOLIS, Ala. (AP) -- A new strain of catfish could improve  
life on the catfish farm. 
</P>
<P>
	The new catfish was genetically engineered for faster growth and  
more efficient use of feed, researchers said. It could be released 
to growers in Mississippi as early as January 2000, said Dr. Ed 
Robinson, coordinator of the Thad Cochran National Warmwater 
Aquaculture Center in Stoneville, Miss. 
</P>
<P>
	The fish, known as USDA 103, may also be released in Alabama  
through an agreement between the states, Robinson said. 
</P>
<P>
	``Primarily, it grows faster, about 20 to 25 percent faster,  
than most strains,'' he said. The fish eats a lot of food but uses 
it more efficiently than other strains. 
</P>
<P>
	Before the fish can be released commercially, it must be  
certified, Robinson said. The release also may be delayed until 
more of the USDA 103 fish reach 3 years old because they spawn 
better then. 
</P>
<P>
	That was only part of the good news for catfish farmers  
attending a recent forum sponsored by the Alabama Catfish Producers 
organization and the Alabama Fish Farming Center. 
</P>
<P>
	Catfish producers had a good 1998 season because feed prices  
remained low, said Hugh Warren, executive vice president of Catfish 
Farmers of America, based in Indianola, Miss. 
</P>
<P>
	Warren said Americans on average eat one pound of catfish per  
year, but that figure is expected to double in the next decade. 
Catfish sales have continued to expand at a pace well beyond the 
population growth, he said. 
</P>
<P>
	Prices for producers are ``pretty good but could be better,''  
said Dickie Odom, chairman of the Alabama Catfish Producers. He 
said some processors are paying 70 cents a pound at the pond site. 
</P>
<P>
	Two of the biggest problems growers encounter are disease and  
birds. New vaccines are being created to control catfish diseases 
that cost farmers millions of dollars per year. 
</P>
<P>
	Research also is under way to battle birds that attack the fish,  
said Frank Boyd, director of the U.S Agriculture Department's 
Wildlife Services facility in Auburn, Ala. 
</P>
<P>
	``A lot of research is going on and more and more ways will be  
used to combat (birds),'' Boyd said. Several scare devices are 
being marketed, ranging from firecrackers to propane gas cannons 
set to go off at intervals, he said. 
</P>
<P>
	------	 
</P>
<P>
	LAKELAND, Fla. (AP) -- Florida's orange harvest is expected to be  
192 million boxes for the 1998-99 season, 2 million boxes less than 
an earlier prediction by federal forecasters. 
</P>
<P>
	But the estimate for frozen concentrated orange juice rose to a  
record 1.62 gallons per 90-pound box, up from 1.6 gallons expected 
in February, according to Florida Citrus Mutual, a 12,000-member 
growers' organization. 
</P>
<P>
	The Agriculture Department revised the February orange-crop  
estimate of 194 million boxes last week after realizing that nearly 
all the state's early and mid-season oranges had been picked and 
made into juice, Florida Mutual said. 
</P>
<P>
	``As the early midseason crop is harvested and processed,  
estimating the amount of fruit actually utilized becomes more 
exact,'' organization President Andy LaVigne noted. ``The 
adjustment is a bookkeeping change for this time of the season.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Florida Citrus Mutual predicts that processors will pack 173.2  
million gallons of frozen concentrated orange juice, up from the 
172.7 million gallons forecast in February. 
</P>
<P>
	``Florida oranges seem to be juicier because we've had  
relatively little adverse weather this winter, LaVigne said. 
``Though it's been dry, growers have irrigated regularly to keep 
their groves in good shape.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Federal forecasters also reduced the state's grapefruit estimate  
by 1 million boxes to 49 million boxes, and the tangelo estimate to 
2.6 million boxes. The early tangerine estimate grew by 50,000 
boxes, to 3.05 million boxes. 
</P>
</TEXT>
