<DOCNO> APW19990314.0087 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-03-14 20:11:15 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> sports </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> No Decision on NFL Expansion </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	PHOENIX (AP) -- NFL owners put off a decision on whether to award  
its next franchise to Los Angeles or Houston, but there were 
indications Los Angeles is the choice. 
</P>
<P>
	A decision on the league's 32nd team is to be made Tuesday or  
Wednesday. A combined meeting of the finance and expansion 
committees on Sunday stopped short of a recommendation. 
</P>
<P>
	``The most we're going to get of this week's meeting is the  
selection of a city,'' league spokesman Joe Browne said. ``We're 
not going to get a stadium site or an ownership group.'' 
</P>
<P>
	That in itself was a hint that Los Angeles is leading in the  
battle for a team by two cities abandoned by the Rams, Raiders and 
Oilers during the mid-1990s franchise free-agency boom. 
</P>
<P>
	On the other hand, the league seems satisfied with Houston's  
stadium and its owner, Robert McNair. Browne later amended his 
comment that no site or owner would be picked to say ``... unless 
it's Houston.'' 
</P>
<P>
	But while the new city will need 24 of 31 votes to be chosen,  
the consensus seems to be it will be Los Angeles, the larger 
market. 
</P>
<P>
	Two groups there are vying for the franchise. One is headed by  
Hollywood agent Michael Ovitz and would build a stadium in Carson, 
south of Los Angeles Airport; the other is headed by Edward Roski 
and would renovate Los Angeles Coliseum. 
</P>
<P>
	Sunday's move came a day after the finance committee put off a  
decision on the proposed $800 million purchase of the Washington 
Redskins by Howard Milstein, which still needs league approval. 
</P>
<P>
	The item of the most general interest this week will be a vote  
on the return of instant replay, which probably won't take until 
late Tuesday or Wednesday. 
</P>
<P>
	The replay proposal under discussion would give coaches two  
challenges per game with extra challenges in the final two minutes 
of each half to be determined by a replay official in the press 
box. The final decision will be made on the field, by the referee. 
</P>
<P>
	After a year of officiating problems, replay seems to have a  
better chance this year than any since 1992, when it was voted out 
after being in effect for six seasons. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW19990314.0088 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-03-14 18:11:40 </DATE_TIME>
