<CATEGORY> sports </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Vicar Wins Florida Derby </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	HALLANDALE, Fla. (AP) -- It's been nine years since Carl Nafzger  
won the Kentucky Derby with Unbridled on his first attempt. On 
Sunday, he was feeling pretty good about his second Derby 
contender, Vicar. 
</P>
<P>
	``If you're not having fun now, you're in trouble,'' Nafzger  
said the morning after Vicar held off Wondertross by a nose to win 
the $750,000 Florida Derby, one of the major steppingstones to the 
May 1 Kentucky Derby. ``This has been a lot of fun, and we're going 
to have a lot more fun now.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Vicar will be shipped to Churchill Downs on March 19, where the  
3-year-old son of Wild Again will prep for the Blue Grass Stakes at 
Keeneland on April 10. 
</P>
<P>
	``There can only be one winner; we have a horse in there, and we  
know it'll be competitive,'' Nafzger said as he stood in front of 
his barn and watched a playful Vicar munch on a cinnamon raisin 
bagel. ``He did what we wanted him to. He dictated and he 
relaxed.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Nafzger allowed Vicar to trot a mile around the track Sunday  
morning, just to ``clean out his system'' after winning a 
four-horse stretch battle that also included third-place finisher 
Cat Thief and fourth-place finisher Certain. 
</P>
<P>
	``Now he'll just walk for a few days,'' the trainer said.  
</P>
<P>
	Nafzger plans to keep on smiling until the next test for his  
gutsy colt. In his previous race, Vicar edged Cat Thief by a neck 
in the Fountain of Youth on Feb. 20. 
</P>
<P>
	Wondertross, who finished second despite a tough trip over the  
1 1/8 miles, is being pointed toward a rematch with Vicar in the Blue 
Grass, trainer Nick Zito said. Wondertross is co-owned by New York 
Yankees boss George Steinbrenner and William Condren. 
</P>
<P>
	Trainer D. Wayne Lukas said third-place finisher Cat Thief would  
also go in the Blue Grass. 
</P>
<P>
	Grits'n Hard Toast, who finished ninth in the field of 10 colts  
and geldings, bled and developed a lung infection, trainer T.V. 
Smith said Sunday. He will be sidelined indefinitely. 
</P>
<P>
	Adonis, who finished sixth, is also trained by Zito, who said  
the Ernie Paragallo-owned colt would run next in the Wood Memorial 
at Aqueduct on April 10. 
</P>
<P>
	While Vicar, a winner in four of six career starts, stamped  
himself as south Florida 's top 3- year-old, the James Tafel-owned 
colt may not be the top Derby prospect. 
</P>
<P>
	Bob Baffert, trying to win an unprecedented third straight  
Kentucky Derby, has at least six top Derby contenders. 
</P>
<P>
	At Santa Anita on Saturday, Baffert's duo of Prime Timber and  
Exploit finished 1-2 in the San Felipe Stakes; and his filly, 
Silverbulletday, won the Fair Ground Oaks in New Orleans. 
</P>
<P>
	In Sunday's Louisiana Derby, 21-1 shot Kimberlite Pipe was the  
upset winner, with Answer Lively second, Ecton Park third and 
Baffert's General Challenge fifth after breaking poorly from the 
gate. Later Sunday, Baffert's filly Excellent Meeting won in the 
Santa Anita Oaks. 
</P>
<P>
	Vicar, ridden by Shane Sellers, went off as the co-second choice  
with Wondertross at 9-2, while Cat Thief was the 9-5 favorite. And 
before Sellers left the jockey's room to climb aboard Vicar, he 
glanced at the odds board at saw his colt was 7-1. 
</P>
<P>
	``I thought I was looking at the wrong horse,'' Sellers said.  
</P>
<P>
	Vicar, racing just off a slow pace, caught leaders Cat Thief and  
Certain at the top of the stretch, and finally grabbed the lead six 
strides from the finish. Then, he withstood Wondertross' gallant 
effort on the outside. 
</P>
<P>
	Certain, third in the Fountain of Youth, was fourth, followed by  
First American, Adonis, Aly's Alley, Casanova Star, Grits'n Hard 
Toast and Valid Trefaire. 
</P>
<P>
	Certain will run next in either the Blue Grass or Arkansas  
Derby, while Aly's Alley is set to go in the Blue Grass. 
</P>
<P>
	The first three finishers in the Florida Derby all have Kentucky  
Derby winning trainers. Nafzger's Unbridled won the Derby in 1990; 
Zito won with Strike the Gold (1991) and Go for Gin (1994), and 
Lukas won with Winning Colors (1988), Thunder Gulch (1995) and 
Grindstone (1996). 
</P>
</TEXT>
