<CATEGORY> financial </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> EU Faces Tough Meeting </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	BRUSSELS, Belgium (AP) -- Even without their controversial  
chairman, European Union finance ministers face a tough meeting 
Monday when such treasured European institutions as duty-free 
shopping and farm subsidies come under renewed attack. 
</P>
<P>
	The surprise resignation Thursday of outspoken German Finance  
Minister Oskar Lafontaine left the Monday's meeting leaderless. It 
was unclear if Lafontaine's successor Hans Eichel, Economics 
Minister Werner Mueller or another German official will hold the 
chair. 
</P>
<P>
	Lafontaine's departure came at a crucial moment in Germany's  
six-month presidency of the EU, as the Union grapples with plans to 
overhaul its finances ahead of a planned expansion into Eastern 
Europe. 
</P>
<P>
	The finance ministers will grapple with a tangled dispute over  
sharing out the EU's $93.5 billion annual budget ahead of a March 
24-25 summit in Berlin, where EU leaders have to thrash out an 
accord on EU spending for the next seven years. 
</P>
<P>
	Central to that debate is a reform of EU farm spending which  
currently eats up half the budget. 
</P>
<P>
	Agriculture ministers from the 15 nations clinched an outline  
deal Thursday that cuts subsidized farm prices by up to 20 percent, 
but provides compensation for farmers that in the short term will 
inflate farm spending. Under this plan, the EU agriculture bill 
would be about $344 billion from 2000 to 2006. 
</P>
<P>
	That has angered some belt-tightening finance ministries.  
``There will be serious pressure for agriculture spending to come 
down again,'' said one national treasury official involved in the 
negotiations. ``The agriculture ministers will not have the final 
word.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Other officials warned hopes of reaching an agreement in Berlin  
will be jeopardized if finance ministers or the leaders themselves 
start to pick holes in the farm deal. 
</P>
<P>
	Britain, Germany and France also will have another go Monday at  
saving duty-free shopping within the EU, but officials from those 
nations acknowledge time is running out for the popular traveler's 
perk. 
</P>
<P>
	All 15 EU nations voted eight years ago to abolish duty-free  
shopping for travelers crossing between EU nations. It goes into 
effect June 30. Most governments have since changed their minds but 
they need unanimity to overturn the decision and Denmark refuses to 
grant a reprieve. 
</P>
<P>
	If the finance ministers fail to agree on a stay of execution  
for duty free, British Prime Minister Tony Blair is expected to 
make a last ditch attempt to save it at the Berlin summit. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
