<CATEGORY> sports </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Sydney Probe Finds IOC Breaches </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	SYDNEY, Australia (AP) -- Sydney's successful bid for the 2000  
Olympics involved numerous breaches of IOC guidelines, an 
independent auditor said Monday. 
</P>
<P>
	But Tom Sheridan criticized the IOC rules governing bids, saying  
they were ``unworkable and have fallen into disrepute.'' 
</P>
<P>
	``The guidelines are unclear and ambiguous in many respects,''  
Sheridan told a news conference Monday. 
</P>
<P>
	SOCOG president Michael Knight said he was pleased with  
Sheridan's investigation into about 3,000 documents related to the 
bid. 
</P>
<P>
	``The Sheridan report shows there is no comparison between what  
occurred in relation to the Salt Lake City bid and what Sydney did 
to win the 2000 Games,'' Knight said Monday. 
</P>
<P>
	``Mr. Sheridan and his team compiled a warts and all report, I'm  
glad there weren't too many warts.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Sheridan said breaches of the IOC guidelines included the value  
of gifts given to IOC delegates, the duration of visits, the number 
of overseas trips made by Sydney bid members to lobby IOC officials 
and assistance in finding jobs for delegates' families. 
</P>
<P>
	Sheridan said under the guidelines Sydney needed to give IOC  
delegates ``red carpet treatment.'' 
</P>
<P>
	If they didn't, ``they may not have necessarily achieved that  
objective,'' of winning the Games. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
