<CATEGORY> usa </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Residents May Buy Housing Project </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	CHICAGO (AP) -- Kelvin Cannon beams with pride as he shows a  
model apartment in the high-rise he and his fellow residents are 
aiming to buy. 
</P>
<P>
	``See how much room there is?'' says Cannon, the building's  
resident maintenance man. ``Nice, huh?'' 
</P>
<P>
	Indeed, the units are spacious, the real estate prime -- and the  
gunfire only occasional. 
</P>
<P>
	This is part of Chicago's notorious Cabrini-Green housing  
project, a good chunk of which already has been torn down to make 
way for townhouses and duplexes that will begin springing up this 
summer. 
</P>
<P>
	But residents of 1230 N. Burling, the building's address and de  
facto name, say they're not about to watch their 15-story, 134-unit 
building meet the wrecking ball and risk never getting one of those 
townhouses. 
</P>
<P>
	They want to buy the building -- and Chicago Housing Authority  
officials say they're likely to sell. 
</P>
<P>
	``They deserve this shot,'' Ed Moses, the agency's deputy  
executive director, says of the resident managers who have been in 
charge of rent collection and upkeep since 1991. 
</P>
<P>
	Moses says they've developed a reputation for reliability, even  
as the neighborhood around them is known for heinous crime. 
</P>
<P>
	That includes the 1992 death of young Dantrell Davis, who was  
struck by a sniper's bullet as he walked hand-in-hand with his 
mother to elementary school. 
</P>
<P>
	Little more than four years later, a 9-year-old who became known  
as Girl X was raped, forced to drink cockroach poison and left for 
dead in another Cabrini-Green building's dank stairwell -- with a 
gang-style pitchfork scrawled across her body. 
</P>
<P>
	It's a history most Chicagoans wouldn't mind seeing torn down  
and carted away. But Burling residents challenge anyone to drive 
past or walk through their building and not see glimmers of hope. 
</P>
<P>
	``We're all lit up at night. You won't see that at the other  
buildings,'' says Cora Moore, the head resident manager and the 
building's grandmother figure. ``The elevators are running. And we 
got heat.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Residents also have built a playground, planted flowers and kept  
the building's hallways and stairwells comparatively free of 
graffiti, broken lights and urine. They've been rewarded with 
millions of dollars worth of government-subsidized upgrades. 
</P>
<P>
	Cannon, a former gang member who's lived at Cabrini-Green most  
of his 35 years, says he's living proof of changes at the building 
he used to terrorize. He returned 10 years ago after spending seven 
years in prison for home invasion and robbery. 
</P>
<P>
	``I said, 'God, let me back into the building to try to redeem  
myself,''' he says. ``Then Cora and the others got a hold of me and 
kept me away from trouble.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Now the resident managers pay him $27,000 a year to maintain the  
building. 
</P>
<P>
	Because of its proximity to downtown and ritzy Lincoln Park, the  
neighborhood is becoming a cultural battleground between low-income 
residents and people who own $300,000 condominiums. 
</P>
<P>
	But even developer Peter Holsten, who'll build the new  
townhouses and duplexes, half of which are committed to low-income 
residents, insists he's not worried about the sooty Burling 
building sticking out like a sore thumb. 
</P>
<P>
	``A lot of the high-rises are just plain ugly,'' Holsten says.  
``But it's not the building -- it's the management. If the 
management does a good job, then you're OK.'' 
</P>
<P>
	The concept of resident ownership isn't exactly new. During the  
Bush administration, it was pushed by then Housing Secretary Jack 
Kemp. 
</P>
<P>
	``The cynic could say it was the federal government just wanting  
to get out of the public housing business,'' says Bill Peterman, a 
geography professor and coordinator of the Fredrick Blum 
Neighborhood Assistance Center at Chicago State University, which 
provides technical assistance to public housing residents who want 
to manage their buildings. 
</P>
<P>
	``Then there's the thought that ... giving the residents the  
responsibility of owning will be a way to make previously 
unworkable housing work.'' 
</P>
<P>
	While dozens of public housing projects nationwide are managed  
by residents, ownership programs have sputtered, with defaulted 
loans and public housing officials having to retake control. 
</P>
<P>
	But residents of 1230 N. Burling say they have a solid plan.  
</P>
<P>
	They're offering the city $50,000 for the building, using a  
40-year loan they propose to pay back with rent and a one-time 
residence fee. Housing officials estimate the building is worth at 
least $1 million. 
</P>
<P>
	They're also promising to put remaining unemployed, able-bodied  
residents -- about half of the 90 lease-holders -- to work or find 
them jobs elsewhere. 
</P>
<P>
	In return, they're asking the federal government to subsidize  
maintenance costs for 10 years. 
</P>
<P>
	Bertha Gilkey, a former public housing resident manager from St.  
Louis who's writing the Burling proposal, says the potential payoff 
makes the residents worth the investment. 
</P>
<P>
	``In 10 years, the taxpayers are outta here,'' Gilkey says.  
``They won't have to pay a dime.'' 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW19990314.0107 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-03-14 14:12:20 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> sports </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Cuban Team To Play in US in May </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	MESA, Ariz. (AP) -- The Baltimore Orioles and Cuba's national  
team will play a return game at Camden Yards on May 3 to complete 
their historic home-and-home exhibition series. 
</P>
<P>
	``I can't tell you how much I'm looking forward to it,''  
commissioner Bud Selig said while attending the Chicago Cubs' 
exhibition game against Seattle on Sunday. ``Baseball is the 
linchpin of the cultural exchange.'' 
</P>
<P>
	A U.S. delegation headed by Sandy Alderson, the executive vice  
president of baseball operations in the commissioner's office, 
negotiated the return game during a three-day trip to Havana that 
ended Saturday. 
</P>
<P>
	Cuba already had agreed to have the Orioles play in Havana on  
March 28, the first time in 40 years a major league team will play 
in Cuba. 
</P>
<P>
	Orioles owner Peter Angelos says his team will use a full  
strength lineup for its game in Havana, which comes eight days 
before Baltimore's season opener against Tampa Bay. 
</P>
<P>
	The return game at Camden Yards comes during an off day in a  
five-game homestand that has Minnesota and the Chicago White Sox 
visit Baltimore. The Orioles could be expected to add minor 
leaguers to their roster for that one, choosing to preserve their 
top pitchers for the games that count. 
</P>
<P>
	Selig plans to attend both games, and baseball officials are  
preparing for hundreds of reporters to attend the game in Havana, 
the first involving a major league team in Cuba since the 
Cincinnati Reds and Los Angeles Dodgers in March 1959. Cuban 
president Fidel Castro, who played baseball in his youth, is 
expected to attend. 
</P>
<P>
	Proceeds from the games will be used mainly to support baseball  
and other sports in the two countries. The use of the money had 
been a sticking point in the negotiations because the Clinton 
administration did not want profits to go to Castro's government. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
