<DOCNO> APW19990314.0110 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-03-14 19:31:22 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> usa </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Brazilian Killed at Waldorf Hotel </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	NEW YORK (AP) -- A Brazilian man who was staying at the opulent  
Waldorf-Astoria Hotel while on a gambling junket at Atlantic City 
was slashed to death in his room, police said Sunday. 
</P>
<P>
	Joao Saboia, 56, left the casinos on Friday with $50,000, police  
sources told Sunday's edition of the New York Post. Investigators 
found $1,300 in the room, the paper said. 
</P>
<P>
	Saboia's body was found in his hotel room late Saturday. He had  
been slashed in the throat. 
</P>
<P>
	The body was found after Saboia failed to rendezvous with his  
companions for a return trip to Atlantic City and did not answer 
his door or phone, the paper said. 
</P>
<P>
	The Waldorf-Astoria and the adjoining Waldorf Towers have been  
New York's premier hotel address for more than half a century. Long 
time residential guests included former President Herbert Hoover 
and World War II hero Gen. Douglas MacArthur. 
</P>
<P>
	Other presidents, including Bill Clinton, often stay there on  
New York visits. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
