<CATEGORY> financial </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Businesses Primed for Spring Break </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	The annual invasion of frostbitten northern college students for  
the rites of spring -- suds, sun and sex -- is being carefully 
watched by businesses that want to add another ``s'' word -- sales -- 
to the spring break lexicon. 
</P>
<P>
	Panama City Beach is expecting 500,000 students on spring break  
between now and the first week of April, while Daytona Beach 
expects to see about 150,000 visitors coming on the heels of 
500,000 bikers, who just left town after the area's annual ``Bike 
Week.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Officials with the Daytona Beach Chamber of Commerce say they  
expect students will spend $45 million over the next few weeks at 
the area's bars, restaurants and hotels Panama City Beach officials 
expect cash flow of about $150 million. 
</P>
<P>
	Businesses are taking the advantage of the student influx,  
touting their wares through various events or setting up 
recruitment booths. 
</P>
<P>
	``We're seeing a lot more on the beach in terms of corporate  
America,'' said Tricia Savard, director of public relations for 
Jiloty Communications in Daytona Beach, which markets spring break. 
</P>
<P>
	Kellogg Co., for instance, is running the Cool Out Cabana on  
Daytona Beach, where it is pushing its Rice Krispies Treats. Other 
companies appearing on the sand at Daytona Beach include discount 
retailer Target Stores Inc., which is sponsoring the 
Coppertone-Target Beach Basketball Tournament and skin care company 
Pond's, which is running a psychics booth. 
</P>
<P>
	At beachside job fairs in both Panama City and Daytona Beach,  
students can wander off the beach in bikinis and possibly land jobs 
with AT&AMP;T Corp., IBM Corp., Memorial Sloan-Kettering Cancer Center, 
the Internal Revenue Service, the Secret Service, 
PricewaterhouseCoopers and dozens of other organizations. 
</P>
<P>
	``We are looking for ways to get to where the students are,''  
Ralph Mobley, manager of college recruiting for IBM in Atlanta. 
``Competition for college students, especially the ones that have 
technical backgrounds, is quite high.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Students with dreams of becoming the next Pamela Anderson can  
participate in The Baywatch Search in Panama City. Daily rounds of 
role playing, acting and lifeguard competition will be used to 
select three men and three women each week to fly to Los Angeles to 
compete for a chance to be in a Baywatch episode. 
</P>
<P>
	Some students in Panama City spoke to Claudia Franco, a business  
analyst who joined IBM a year ago after graduating from the 
University of California, Davis, with a degree in mathematics. She 
was sent to tell them about her experiences. 
</P>
<P>
	``It's a great place to work,'' she said. ``Most students were  
very interested.'' 

</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
