<CATEGORY> sports </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Van Gundy's Job Security Questioned </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	NEW YORK (AP) -- Jeff Van Gundy's job security seemed somewhat  
tenuous Sunday night after NBC reported that he would be fired if 
the Knicks lost to the Hornets. 
</P>
<P>
	Van Gundy was watching the Nets-Heat game during the afternoon  
when NBC commentator Peter Vescey, citing unnamed sources, said Van 
Gundy's job was in jeopardy. 
</P>
<P>
	Van Gundy tried to make light of the report, but also admitted  
that he had spoken to Knicks brass after it aired. 
</P>
<P>
	Also, Van Gundy somehow knew that his career coaching record  
included 83 losses. 
</P>
<P>
	``Let's face it, until they fire you, they're never going to say  
`You know what, we're thinking of firing (you). We're going to give 
it a couple more games to see.' So, it's part of the business. And 
if we play like we did in Chicago, someone's got to pay,'' Van 
Gundy said. 
</P>
<P>
	The Knicks went into Sunday night's game against Charlotte with  
an 11-9 record, having lost six of their last nine -- including a 
hideous performance Friday night at Chicago when they scored five 
points in the second quarter, 22 in the first half and 33 in the 
first three quarters. 
</P>
<P>
	``Believe me, no one is more critical of me than me. It tears my  
guts out about that game in Chicago because I feel I'm better coach 
than that, I take a lot of pride in my work, just as I have since 
I've been here for 10 years.'' 
</P>
<P>
	A few of the Knicks players were surprised to hear that their  
coach's job status was in question. 
</P>
<P>
	``I don't think there's ever been a more prepared coach that  
I've ever played for than Jeff,'' Allan Houston said. ``I don't 
know what more else he can do.'' 
</P>
<P>
	The past few days have been rocky for the rest of the team, too.  
</P>
<P>
	Latrell Sprewell and Chris Childs were offered to Minnesota on  
Thursday when the Knicks tried to acquire Stephon Marbury, the team 
called players-only meeting after the loss in Chicago on Friday, 
and the players learned Saturday that veteran Dennis Scott, whose 
minutes were severely limited by Van Gundy, had been released. 
</P>
<P>
	Van Gundy, whose office wall is adorned with some of the tabloid  
back pages that have previously foretold of his eminent departure 
(``Bad Noose for Van Gundy'' and ``The Whiner Within''), joked that 
he had almost been fired every year. 
</P>
<P>
	``The first year it was right after I got the job, the second  
year it was like 12 games, last year it was 15, so we've waited too 
long this year, it's been 20 games.'' 
</P>
<P>
	But in those years, Van Gundy was much more quick to dismiss or  
ridicule those reports. 
</P>
<P>
	On Sunday, his demeanor was different.  
</P>
<P>
	He even pointed out that he learned he got the Knicks coaching  
job from reading it in Vecsey's newspaper column. 
</P>
<P>
	``He's got a lot of sources in New York. That's just how it is  
here,'' he said. ``It's OK. It would be different if I didn't know 
what I was getting into. I knew what I was getting into.'' 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
