<CATEGORY> sports </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Pataki Urges Probe of Title Bout </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	ALBANY, N.Y. (AP) -- Gov. George Pataki will ask the New York  
state Athletic Commission to look into the controversial draw 
declared in the Lennox Lewis-Evander Holyfield heavyweight 
championship fight. 
</P>
<P>
	Pataki said Sunday that his administration has worked hard to  
bring championship boxing back to Madison Square Garden. 
</P>
<P>
	``But it has to be done in a way that upholds the integrity of  
the game and people's confidence in the sport,'' he said in the 
aftermath of the fight Saturday night. ``If this decision 
jeopardizes that, then it's certainly something we should look at 
to try to make sure that in the future we can be confident that the 
judges are going to be objective judges and not have any ulterior 
motive. 
</P>
<P>
	``I wouldn't say that they necessarily did in this case, but  
it's certainly something the boxing commission should take a hard 
look at.'' 
</P>
<P>
	The Lewis-Holyfield heavyweight reunification fight was declared  
a draw, despite what most ringside observers saw as domination by 
Lewis. Statistics on landed punches showed Lewis with an 
overwhelming edge, and the decision was roundly booed by the a 
sellout crowd of 21,284. Their tickets had face values ranging from 
$1,500 to $100. 
</P>
<P>
	Pataki said he did not watch the fight but was being informed  
Saturday night of its progress through the first eight rounds. He 
was told at that point that Lewis had won every round, according to 
Pataki. 
</P>
<P>
	The governor said on Sunday afternoon that he did not know how  
the fight turned out or about the disputed decision. 
</P>
<P>
	``This is the first I've heard of a controversy,'' he told  
reporters Sunday afternoon after attending a reception for minority 
and female entrepreneurs in Albany. ``They called it a draw?'' 
</P>
<P>
	The state Athletic Commission sanctioned the event and selected  
the referee, Arthur Mercante Jr., spokesman Scott Trent said 
Sunday. 
</P>
<P>
	The judges are ``essentially presented to the commission for  
approval'' by the three boxing organizations whose heavyweight 
titles are held by either Lewis or Holyfield, the World Boxing 
Association, the International Boxing Federation and the World 
Boxing Council, Trent said. 
</P>
<P>
	Those organizations have called for a mandatory rematch.  
</P>
<P>
	Trent made it clear Sunday that the commission was responsible  
for the referee's work in the fight, but not the judges'. 
</P>
<P>
	``The commission is very satisfied with the performance of  
Arthur Mercante Jr.,'' Trent said Sunday. ``Ultimately, the judges 
were selected by the sanctioning bodies with the approval of the 
Athletic Commission. I think that speaks for itself.'' 
</P>
<P>
	The state Athletic Commission is now chaired by Mel Southard,  
who took over after former heavyweight champion Floyd Patterson 
resigned in April 1998 after acknowledging that he was having 
memory problems. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
