<CATEGORY> entertainment </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> 'Providence' Star Won't Change Name </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	NEW YORK (AP) -- Her name might be tough for some people to  
pronounce, but Melina Kanakaredes of ``Providence'' doesn't care 
who gets tongue-tied trying to say it. 
</P>
<P>
	``Never even thought about it,'' Kanakaredes, 31, says in the  
April issue of US magazine when asked if she ever considered 
changing her name. ``People made that suggestion and I laughed. I 
want my agent to get me in the door and my talent to get me the 
job. 
</P>
<P>
	``I think of my grandfather coming over from Greece when he was  
18 or 19, and it makes me proud that our name is on movies and TV 
shows. It would be kind of a bummer to make it now and be somebody 
else.'' 
</P>
<P>
	The star of the new hit medical drama appeared in such films as  
``Rounders'' and ``The Long Kiss Goodnight'' before deciding to 
give television a try, even turning down a role on ``Law and 
Order'' as she wavered about whether to do TV or films. 
</P>
<P>
	``I was called by (then NBC entertainment President) Warren  
Littlefield,'' she says. ``I said to him, `My whole life, my 
parents said, `go to the dance with the first guy who asks you; 
it's the right way to do it.' Well, I just want to wait and go to 
the dance with the guy I really want to go with now. 
</P>
<P>
	``So I signed a development deal with NBC saying that if there  
was an amazing project that came across my desk, I would definitely 
do it.'' 
</P>
<P>
	The waiting paid off for Kanakaredes (Can-uh-CAR-ee-dees) with  
``Providence,'' a family-oriented drama in which she plays a 
plastic surgeon. Despite critical reviews, it has become a ratings 
hit. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
