<CATEGORY> usa </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Man Jumps Out of Moving Ambulance </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	ORLANDO, Fla. (AP) -- A man being transported to the hospital  
following a heroin overdose jumped from an ambulance going 35 mph 
and ran into the woods as cars braked and swerved to avoid him. 
</P>
<P>
	Matthew Heffelfinger, 31, was being transported Friday when  
``all of a sudden, he said, `I don't want to go,''' said Kathy 
Putnam, spokeswoman for Rural Metro Ambulance. ``While he's doing 
this, he's tearing off the straps from the stretcher and pulling 
out his IVs.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Before calling the ambulance, Heffelfinger's grandmother found  
him on his bed, blue in the face and unconscious next to a syringe 
and a tablespoon. 
</P>
<P>
	Paramedics gave him an injection of Narcan, a heroin antidote,  
according to emergency medical personnel and Orange County 
sheriff's reports. 
</P>
<P>
	In the ambulance, Heffelfinger got up, spraying blood and  
intravenous fluids from the tubes pulled from his arms, Putnam 
said. That's when he opened the rear door and jumped. 
</P>
<P>
	``He's OK,'' Florence Heffelfinger, the man's grandmother, said  
Saturday. ``It's over, and let it drop.'' 
</P>
<P>
	It wasn't clear whether Heffelfinger might face any charges.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
