<CATEGORY> sports </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> TCU Dreams of Reaching NYC for NIT </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	There's no doubt that every member of the Texas Christian  
basketball team would rather be playing this week in the NCAA 
tournament. 
</P>
<P>
	But a late-season slump cost the Horned Frogs their shot at that  
event. Now, they're trying to make the most of their time in the 
NIT which resumes with five second-round games Monday night. 
</P>
<P>
	TCU (20-10) is at home against Nebraska (20-12). In Monday's  
other second-round games, Wake Forest (17-13) is at Xavier (22-10), 
Old Dominion (25-8) at Butler (21-9), Princeton (21-7) at North 
Carolina State (19-13) and Wyoming (18-9) at Oregon (17-11). 
</P>
<P>
	The second round concludes Tuesday with Clemson (17-14) at  
Rutgers (19-12), Colorado (18-14) at Colorado State (18-10), and 
California (18-11) at DePaul (18-12). 
</P>
<P>
	TCU knows the NIT offers a trip to New York for the semifinals  
and final and that keeps the Horned Frogs going. 
</P>
<P>
	As guard Ryan Carroll practiced jump shots in practice this  
week, he made a proposition to a teammate. 
</P>
<P>
	``If I get this, we're going to New York,'' Carroll said.  
</P>
<P>
	The shot went in.  
</P>
<P>
	During games, not enough shots went in for the Horned Frogs this  
season. Coming off a 27-6 season and an NCAA berth, expectations 
were high for this season's team. 
</P>
<P>
	But the team built around preseason All-America forward Lee  
Nailon and another 6-foot-9 forward, Marquise Gainous, stumbled 
down the stretch and lost in the first round of the Western 
Athletic Conference tournament. 
</P>
<P>
	``For the next few years, until something better comes along,  
last year's team is the bar we judge everybody by,'' TCU coach 
Billy Tubbs said. ``This year's team didn't raise the bar.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Nebraska and TCU had contrasting first-round victories in the  
NIT. 
</P>
<P>
	The Cornhuskers, winners of the NIT in 1996, defeated UNLV 68-55  
as Cookie Belcher scored 17 points and Larry Florence added 16, 
while the Horned Frogs edged Kansas State 72-71 as Nailon scored 
22, 16 in the first half. 
</P>
<P>
	Nebraska coach Danny Nee sees similarities with Tubbs' TCU team.  
</P>
<P>
	``With Billy and my team too, if you shoot the ball well, then  
it doesn't matter what you do, it looks good,'' Nee said. ``When it 
doesn't go, well, that's another story.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Like TCU, Butler, Xavier and Oregon all had close wins in the  
first round. 
</P>
<P>
	Butler advanced with a 51-50 victory over Bradley, Xavier nipped  
Toledo 86-84 and Oregon downed Georgia Tech 67-64. 
</P>
<P>
	LaVall Jordan's basket in the closing seconds gave Butler the  
victory at Bradley. James Posey scored 20 points, including a key 
3-pointer down the stretch, as Xavier won at Toledo. 
</P>
<P>
	A.D. Smith's two free throws with 1:19 left gave Oregon the lead  
for good and the Ducks won their first postseason game since 1988. 
</P>
</TEXT>
